{"title_page": "Hans-Joachim Brauske", "text_new": "{{short description|German boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Hans-Joachim Brauske\n| full_name      = \n| image          = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-B0918-0011-003, Karpati, Brauske.jpg\n| caption        = \n| nationality    = German\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|10|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Lauchhammer]], [[Brandenburg]], Germany\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Hans-Joachim Brauske''' (born 12 October 1943) is a German [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Middleweight|men's middleweight]] event at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/br/hans-joachim-brauske-1.html |title=Hans-Joachim Brauske Olympic Results |accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brauske, Hans-Joachim}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of East Germany]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:People from Lauchhammer]]\n{{Germany-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Hans-Joachim Brauske\n| full_name      = \n| image          = Bundesarchiv Bild 183-B0918-0011-003, Karpati, Brauske.jpg\n| caption        = \n| nationality    = German\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1943|10|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Brandenburg]], Germany\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Hans-Joachim Brauske''' (born 12 October 1943) is a German [[boxing|boxer]]. He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1972 Summer Olympics \u2013 Middleweight|men's middleweight]] event at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/br/hans-joachim-brauske-1.html |title=Hans-Joachim Brauske Olympic Results |accessdate=18 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brauske, Hans-Joachim}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of East Germany]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1972 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:People from Lauchhammer]]\n{{Germany-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Darwinek", "label": "safe", "comment": "/per the Sports-Reference link in the article/", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans-Joachim_Brauske"}
{"title_page": "Dee Bradley Baker", "text_new": "{{short description|American voice actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Dee Bradley Baker\n|image = Dee Bradley Baker by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|caption = Baker at [[WonderCon|WonderCon 2016]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|8|31}}  \n|birth_place = [[Bloomington, Indiana]], U.S.\n|home_town = [[Greeley, Colorado]], U.S.\n|residence = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S. <!-- Twitter indicates Los Angeles -->\n|alma_mater = [[Colorado College]]\n| agent = Cynthia McLean<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=CRS20070307.2.10.3|title=Talent Agent Lectures for Mary Pickford Series | volume = 93 | number = 3| newspaper = Corsair Newspaper \u2013 [[Santa Monica College]] | first=Barbara |last=Szabo | date = March 7, 2007 | via= California Digital Newspaper Collection |accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\">{{cite web | url = http://www.toonzone.net/2014/09/toonzone-interviews-dee-bradley-baker-steve-blum-speak-boxtroll/ | title = Toonzone Interviews Dee Bradley Baker & Steve Blum on How to Speak Boxtroll | date = September 25, 2014 | work = Toonzone | first = Ed |last=Liu }}</ref>\n|occupation = Voice actor\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present <!-- Legends of the Hidden Temple was his first major TV role -->\n|other_names =\n| spouse= {{marriage|Michelle Baker|1990}}\n| children = 2\n|URL = {{URL|http://www.deebaker.com}}\n}}\n'''Dee Bradley Baker''' (born August 31, 1962)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.wired.com/geekdad/2011/08/happy-birthday-dee-bradley-baker-2/|title=Happy Birthday, Dee Bradley Baker!|work=GeekDad|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired.com]] | date=August 31, 2011 | accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><!-- confirms only month and day --><ref name=\"sentinel 1991\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-30/news/9108300714_1_dee-baker-fortner-side-story|title=Baker Fits The Bill In 'West Side Story'|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publication-date=August 30, 1991|first= Laurie |last=Whitmore|quote= At the age of 28, Baker is among the lucky minority of entertainers who can call themselves working actors}}</ref><!-- confirms year --> is an American [[Voice acting|voice actor]]. His major roles, many of which feature his vocalizations of animals, include animated series such as ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'', ''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]'', ''[[Gravity Falls]]'', ''[[Steven Universe]]'', ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'',  ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'', ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', ''[[Ben 10]]'', ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'' and ''[[The 7D]]'', live action series such as ''[[Legends of the Hidden Temple]]'' and ''[[Shop 'til You Drop]]'', films such as ''[[The Boxtrolls]]'' and ''[[Space Jam]]'' and video games such as ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'', ''[[Gears of War]]'', ''[[Viewtiful Joe (series)|Viewtiful Joe]]'', ''[[Spore (2008 video game)|Spore]]'', and ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBaker was born in [[Bloomington, Indiana]] to Buddy and Nancy Baker,<ref name=\"nancy obit\">{{cite web|url=https://obittree.com/obituary/us/colorado/fort-collins/allnutt-funeral-service/nancy-baker/898848/|title=Nancy Ann Baker Obituary \u2013 December 21, 1935 - April 24, 2007 |author=|date=|work=ObitTree|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"greeley tribune\">{{cite web|url=https://www.greeleytribune.com/news/vocal-vocation-greeley-native-makes-a-living-voicing-characters-in-films-tv-shows/|title=Vocal vocation: Greeley native makes a living voicing characters in films, TV shows|first=Dan | last=England | date=February 14, 2007 | work=Greeley Tribune | access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> and grew up in [[Greeley, Colorado]].<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> He started performing at age nine and steadily worked in musicals, operas, plays and stand-up. As a child he was a fan of ''[[Star Trek]]'', ''[[Star Wars]]'', [[Frank Zappa]] and the ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'', and also liked insects, arthropods and dinosaurs.<ref name=\"VO studio interview\">{{cite video | title = VO Studio: Dee Baker | author = Zev Suissa | work = VO Studio | date = April 11, 2013 }}</ref> He graduated from [[University Charter Schools (Colorado)|University High School]] in 1981<ref name=\"greeley tribune\"/> and received a [[Boettcher Scholarship]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.boettcherfoundation.org/home/scholarships/graduated-scholars/featured-scholar-profiles | title = Featured Scholar Profiles \u2013 Under Water is a Good Thing | work = [[Boettcher Foundation]] | accessdate=September 17, 2014 }}</ref> \n\nHe attended [[Colorado College]] in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], where he studied philosophy, biology, fine arts and German, the last of which he studied overseas for a year at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]].<ref name=\"emily interview\">{{cite video | url = http://www.comicmix.com/2013/08/13/emily-s-whitten-dee-bradley-baker-is-an-animal/ | title = Emily S. Whitten: Dee Bradley Baker is an Animal! | work = ComicMix | date = August 11, 2013 | first = Emily S. |last=Whitten }} \u2013 includes YouTube interview</ref> He was involved in local theater productions and singing groups. After graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in philosophy, he was involved in many community theatre projects, including a sketch movie that aired on local public television.<ref name=\"honorary bio\">{{cite web | url = http://www.coloradocollege.edu/dotAsset/247c7215-4c99-48d2-97f1-250384649fda.pdf |title = Dee Bradley Baker '86 | work = [[Colorado College]] | accessdate = September 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Dee Bradley Baker by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Baker at the 2010 [[San Diego Comic Con]]]]\nBaker moved to Orlando in 1989 to work on an improv sketch comedy show titled \"The Anacomical Players\" at [[EPCOT Center]]'s [[Wonders of Life]] pavilion and joined various projects for Disney and Universal Studios.<ref name=\"sentinel 1991\"/><ref name=\"honorary bio\"/><ref name=\"D23\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7XbceE2LTY|title=Full Voices of the Disney Theme Parks presentation from D23 Expo 2011|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=September 19, 2012|format=YouTube|work=Attractions Magazine}} \u2013 4 minutes in for Pirates, 15 minutes in for Boba Fett <!-- boba fett self-claim during panel interview--></ref> His first major experience on national television was on the Nickelodeon game show ''[[Legends of the Hidden Temple]]'', where he was not only the announcer, but also the giant talking rock-god Olmec.<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/><ref name=\"twitter legends\">{{cite tweet| user = deebradleybaker| number = 338294639410941952 <!-- https://twitter.com/deebradleybaker/status/338294639410941952 -->| title = \"''Legends of the Hidden Temple'' was my 1st show. Forever a fan favorite! RT @The90sLife: Olmec #beststatuesofthe90s\"| author = Dee Bradley Baker| date = May 25, 2013| accessdate = December 13, 2014}}</ref> He portrayed Olmec with a \"big, booming, loud, god-like voice\". During parts of the show, he would narrate a legend, and then ask the kid contestants related trivia questions. The show lasted three seasons and 120 episodes. When host [[Kirk Fogg]] moved to Los Angeles, he was encouraged to move there as well.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.buzzfeed.com/jaimieetkin/legends-of-the-hidden-temple-kirk-fogg-olmec | title = The Legend Of \"Legends Of The Hidden Temple,\" As Told By Kirk Fogg and Olmec | work = [[BuzzFeed]] | first=Jamie | last=Etkin | date = September 11, 2013 }}</ref> In 2016, he and Fogg reprised their roles for a [[Legends of the Hidden Temple (film)|live action television movie adaptation]] of the show.<ref name=\"variety legends 2016\">{{cite web |author=McClendon, Lamarco |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/tv-news-legends-of-the-hidden-temple-movie-dee-bradley-baker-rosewood-brian-austin-green-1201801425/ |title=TV News Roundup: 'Legends of the Hidden Temple' Revival Brings Back Original Olmec; Brian Austin Green Joins 'Rosewood' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBaker moved to Southern California in time for the [[1994 Northridge earthquake]]. He got involved in voice-over work; his first major character was Cow & Chicken's dad in the ''[[Cow & Chicken]]'' and ''[[I Am Weasel]]'' cartoons.<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> His first feature film voice-over was on the basketball/Looney Tunes-themed movie ''[[Space Jam]]'' where he voiced [[Daffy Duck]], [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Taz]] and [[Bully for Bugs|Toro]].<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> He did voice work for various episodic and recurring cartoon characters on ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]'',<ref name=\"jonny quest\">{{cite AV media | at=Closing credits | title=Future Rage | series=The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest | serieslink=The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest | season=1 | number=24}}</ref> ''[[Johnny Bravo]]'', ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'',<ref name=\"dexter3-1\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=Streaky Clean/A Dad Cartoon/Sole Brother | date=2001 | series=Dexter's Laboratory | serieslink=Dexter's Laboratory | season=3 | number=1}}</ref> ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''<ref name=\"brooks-1285\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=1285}}</ref> and ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]''.<ref name=\"powerpuff 4-4\">{{cite episode | number=4 | title=Him Diddle Riddle | series=The Powerpuff Girls | serieslink=The Powerpuff Girls | airdate=2002-06-21 | season=4}}</ref> He voiced starring characters Og in ''[[Mike, Lu & Og]]''<ref name=\"brooks-895\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=895}}</ref> and [[Bagheera]] in the second season of ''[[Jungle Cubs]]''.<ref name=\"terrace-549\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=549}}</ref> In 2001, he added voice roles for Sanjay, Binky and other characters for ''[[The Fairly OddParents]]''<ref name=\"terrace-322\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=322}}</ref><ref name=\"btva\"/> and co-starred as Mandy's father on ''[[Billy and Mandy]]''.<ref name=\"terrace-418\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=418}}</ref><ref name=\"btva\"/> He had a lead role as [[Codename: Kids Next Door#Kids Next Door|Numbuh 4]] in ''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]''.<ref name=\"brooks-268\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=268}}</ref> On the live action front, he became the co-host and announcer for the game show ''[[Shop 'til You Drop]]'' which spanned several hundred episodes when it resumed broadcasting on the [[Television networks preceding Freeform|Family Channel]] and on the [[Ion Television#Pax TV (1998\u20132005)|Pax television network]], until a series retool in 2003; it was produced by Stone Stanley Entertainment, which had earlier co-produced ''Legends of the Hidden Temple''.<ref name=\"brooks-1230\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|pp=1230\u20131231}}</ref> He also had a recurring role as Phil Berg in the Nickelodeon sitcom series ''[[The Journey of Allen Strange]]'' where he plays a crazed journalist who tries to expose Allen's identity as a space alien.<ref name=\"brooks-717\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=717}}</ref>\n\n<!-- animal characters -->\nStarting with gigs on ''[[The Wild Thornberrys]]'', he voiced an assortment of animal characters, which would become one of his specialties.<ref name=\"btva\"/> He voiced Pig George in the live action animal film ''[[My Brother the Pig]]''.<ref name=\"my brother the pig movie\">{{cite video| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WfrO3fLP8zc | format=YouTube | author = [[FilmRise|FilmRise movies]] | title = My Brother the Pig \u2013 Starring Scarlett Johansson \u2013 Full Movie | at=1:28:48 }}</ref> Baker has also been involved with television shows for younger children including: ''[[Dora the Explorer]]'' where he provided animal sounds;<ref name=\"dora\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=Boots Cuddly Dinosaur | series=Dora the Explorer | serieslink=Dora the Explorer}}</ref> ''[[Mickey Mouse Clubhouse]]'' where he voices [[Mickey Mouse Clubhouse#Boo Boo Chicken|Boo Boo Chicken]];<ref name=\"mmc 5-1\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=Mickey Goes Fishing | series=Mickey Mouse Clubhouse | serieslink=Mickey Mouse Clubhouse | season=1 | number=5}}</ref> ''[[Curious George (TV series)|Curious George]]'' where he voices Gnocchi;<ref name=\"gnocchi\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=No Knowing Gnocchi / Here Comes the Tide | series=Curious George | serieslink=Curious George (TV series) | season=6 | number=10}}</ref> ''[[My Friends Tigger & Pooh]]'' where he voices [[List of Winnie-the-Pooh characters#Buster|Buster]] the dog<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdizzy.com/frankenweenie.html|title=Frankenweenie Blu-ray 3D, Blu-ray & DVD Review | work = DVDizzy.com |accessdate=September 30, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Jake and the Neverland Pirates]]'' (airing on [[Disney Junior]]) where he voices Tick-Tock the crocodile.<ref name=\"btva\"/> In ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'' where he voiced the creatures [[Appa (character)|Appa]] and [[Momo (Avatar: The Last Airbender)|Momo]]<ref name=\"brooks-88\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=88}}</ref> and would soon voice many other creatures in the series as well as its sequel, ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'', where he voices Naga, Pabu and Oogi. He voiced in the ''[[American Dragon: Jake Long]]''<ref name=\"jake long\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jeffgoode.com/tv/americandragon/02season/219.htm | title=American Dragon: Jake Long \u2013 episode 219 \u2013 \"A Ghost Story\" \u2013 by Chris Nee | work=Jeff Goode Official Website | accessdate=October 4, 2014 | last=Goode | first=Jeff | authorlink=Jeff Goode}}</ref> and ''[[Ben 10]]'' series, the latter of which he voiced many alien creatures such as [[List of Ben 10 aliens#Stinkfly|Stinkfly]] and [[Wildmutt]], as well as some of the transformations.<ref name=\"btva\" /><ref name=\"brooks-123\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=123}}</ref> He also voiced in the ''Ben 10'' sequels such as ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]'',<ref name=\"terrace-89\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=89}}</ref> ''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]'' and ''[[Ben 10: Omniverse]]'', as well as its live-action adaptation.<ref name=\"btva\"/><ref name=\"formspring\">{{cite news | url=http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/340540854995280906 | title=Will Humungousaur, Cannonbolt, Spidermonkey be voiced by Dee Bradley Baker in Omniverse, or will it be by someone else? | work=[[Formspring]] | last=Wyatt | first=Derrick J. | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412185629/http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/340540854995280906 | archivedate=April 12, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"formspring2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/349221639273073039 | title=What made everyone decide to have a variety of voice actors voicing the Ben 10 aliens? (Dee Bradley Baker voicing every alien besides Rath was the dumbest idea in the universe...) | last=Wyatt | first=Derrick J. | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412185630/http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/349221639273073039 | archivedate=April 12, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Derrick J. Wyatt, who was the art director for ''Omniverse'', noted that they had to allow other voice actors to do some of the aliens in the later series because Baker was doing almost all of them and some of the characters were putting a strain on his throat.<ref name=\"formspring2\"/> Outside of television, he provided the voice of [[Captain Jack Sparrow]]'s talking parrot in the refurbished ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' rides at Disneyland and the [[Magic Kingdom]].<ref name=\"D23\"/><ref name=\"dis unplugged\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disunplugged.com/2010/05/21/star-wars-weekends-send-in-the-clones/|title=Star Wars Weekends: Send In The Clones! - The DIS Unplugged Disney Podcast|author=|date=|website=www.disunplugged.com|accessdate=November 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!--- need more details on how he portrays perry -->\nIn 2007, Baker got the role of [[Perry the Platypus]] in the Disney series ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''. At the San Diego Comic-Con 2013 panel, Baker mentioned that when he auditioned, he was asked to provide three different creature sounds, regardless of whether it actually sounded like a platypus, of which one was selected as Perry's characteristic sound.<ref name=\"comic-con 2013 phineas and ferb\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2-adkax_QLA|title=Full Phineas and Ferb panel at San Diego Comic-Con 2013 including Marvel, Star Wars|format=YouTube|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Perry has become a [[breakout character]] for the series,<ref name=\"star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118011690.html?categoryId=1050&cs=1|title='Phineas' star Perry makes mark on auds|author=Littleton, Cynthia|date=November 20, 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 26, 2009}}</ref> with Baker appearing at multiple Comic-Con panels for the show.<ref name=\"comic-con 2013 phineas and ferb\"/> In 2014, Perry was nominated for a [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Award]] for Best Animal Sidekick. Coincidentally, another one of Baker's voiced characters, Waddles the pet pig in ''[[Gravity Falls]]'', was nominated for the same category.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/kids_choice_awards_2014_full_winners_list-2014-03 | title = Kids' Choice Awards 2014 Full Winners List | work = [[Zap2It]] | first=Laurel | last=Brown | date = March 20, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n<!-- regular animation more details regarding klaus -->\nBaker would continue to do regular voice-over roles. In 2005, he landed a role as [[Klaus Heissler]], an Olympic ski jumper from Germany who was [[Body swap|body-swapped]] into a goldfish, in the primetime cartoon sitcom ''[[American Dad!]]'',<ref name=\"ovguide1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ovguide.com/roger-9202a8c04000641f80000000008d8419 | title=Roger Video &#124; Movie Clips & Character Interview | publisher=Ovguide.com | accessdate=April 9, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521175723/http://www.ovguide.com/roger-9202a8c04000641f80000000008d8419 | archivedate=May 21, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/therootdc/post/american-dad-one-of-the-most-sophisticated-mainstream-shows-on-african-american-culture/2012/10/08/e8374cba-051d-11e2-91e7-2962c74e7738_blog.html | title='American Dad': One of the most sophisticated mainstream shows on African American culture \u2013 The Root DC Live | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=October 8, 2012 | accessdate=April 1, 2013 | last=McEwen | first=Lauren}}</ref> which has run over eleven seasons on Fox and TBS. In an interview with Pop Break, Baker said that he liked playing Klaus because he loves the German language, the part was well written, and it is light duty on his voice. He compared the [[Read-through|table reads]] to being on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]''.<ref name=\"pop break\">{{cite web | url=http://pop-break.com/2014/11/03/american-dad-interview-series-baker-macfarlane/ | title=American Dad Interview Series: Dee Bradley Baker & Rachael MacFarlane | date=November 3, 2014 | work = Pop-Break.com | first=Luke | last=Kalamar }}</ref> He participated in ''American Dad'' panels at [[San Diego Comic-Con International|San Diego Comic-Con]] 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2010/06/comiccon-2010.html|title='Caprica' will be there, 'Game of Thrones' will not: The Comic-Con lineup|publisher=|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/06/13/glee-cast-and-creators-return-to-comic-con-2012-in-star-studded-panel-saturday-july-14/137885/|title='Glee' Cast and Creators Return to Comic-Con 2012 in Star-Studded Panel Saturday, July 14 - Ratings - TVbytheNumbers.Zap2it.com|work=TVbytheNumbers|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> and 2014;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comic-con.org/cci/saturday|title=Comic-Con 2014 Saturday Programs|work=Comic-Con International: San Diego|accessdate=October 18, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023175201/http://www.comic-con.org/cci/saturday | archivedate=October 23, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> and the [[New York Comic-Con]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/american-dad-article-1.1967982|title=New York Comic Con 2014: 'American Dad's' move to TBS brings strong story with more dirty words to new season|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> His voicing of council member Tarrlok in ''Korra'' garnered a nomination for the Behind the Voice Actors (BTVA) Voice Acting Award in 2012.<ref name=\"about basile\">{{cite web | url=http://animatedtv.about.com/od/clonewars/p/Dee-Bradley-Baker.htm | title=Dee Bradley Baker | work=Animated TV at About.com | accessdate=September 22, 2014 | last=Basile | first=Nancy | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924044959/http://animatedtv.about.com/od/clonewars/p/Dee-Bradley-Baker.htm | archivedate=September 24, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=832}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Perlmutter|2014|p=367}}</ref><ref name=\"btva korra\">{{cite web | url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/btva-awards/2012/television/ | title=2012 Annual BTVA Voice Acting Awards | work=Behind the Voice Actors | accessdate=September 22, 2014}}</ref> In addition to television shows, Baker voiced characters in many animated and live action animation films, including some of the classic ghost monsters in ''[[Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed]]'',<ref name=\"scooby movie 2\">{{cite web | url = https://www.allmovie.com/movie/scooby-doo-2-monsters-unleashed-v286521/cast-crew | title = Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed (2004) \u2013 Cast and Crew | work = AllMovie | accessdate=September 23, 2014 }}</ref> Maurice in ''[[Happy Feet]]'',<ref name=\"btva\"/> He had roles in the ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]]'' TV series and its direct-to-video releases.<ref name=\"btva\"/>\n\n<!--- star wars: also need more details on the troopers --->\nBaker was involved in the ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' film released in 2008 and [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|its television series]] afterwards which ran for six seasons. He provided the voices for not only the characters [[Captain Rex]] and Commander Cody, but also all the supporting [[Clone Troopers]],<ref name=\"about basile\"/><ref name=\"awn clones\">{{cite web | url=http://www.awn.com/news/dee-bradley-baker-discusses-voicing-clones-star-wars-clone-wars | title=Dee Bradley Baker Discusses Voicing The Clones in Star Wars: The Clone Wars | work=Animation World Magazine | date=October 23, 2008 | last=Moody | first=Annemarie}}</ref><ref name=\"annie awards clones\">{{cite web | url=http://annieawards.org/39th-annie-awards | title=39th Annie Awards | work=[[Annie Awards]] | accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"voicing an army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonzone.net/2011/09/new-voicing-an-army-bts-clip-from-star-wars-the-clone-wars/|title=New \"Voicing an Army\" BTS Clip from \"Star Wars: The Clone Wars\"|work=Toon Zone News}}</ref><ref name=\"ign rex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/09/06/star-wars-the-clone-wars-whats-next-for-rex|title=Star Wars: The Clone Wars - What's Next for Rex?|work=IGN|date=September 6, 2011|first=Eric|last=Goldman}}</ref> the last of which he received an [[Annie Award]] nomination for Voice Acting in a Television Production in 2012.<ref name=\"annie awards clones\"/> He reprised the role of Captain Rex in ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', beginning with its second season. He also provided the voice of [[Boba Fett]] for ''[[Star Tours \u2013 The Adventures Continue]]''.<ref name=\"D23\"/> In the 2011 ''[[Family Guy]]'' episode \"[[It's a Trap!]]\", a parody of the ''Star Wars'' film ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'', he voiced Klaus as [[Admiral Ackbar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Manco |first=Emanuele |title=Family Guy: It's a Trap |work=Fantasy Magazine |date=December 24, 2010 |url=http://www.fantasymagazine.it/notizie/13738/family-guy-it-s-a-trap/ |language=Italian |accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- video games -->\nIn the video game world, Baker reprised his roles in Cartoon Network and Nickelodeon's multitude of show-related game releases. He also voiced Gravemind in ''[[Halo 2]]'' and ''[[Halo 3]],''<ref name=\"btva\"/> and the title character Joe in the ''[[Viewtiful Joe (series)|Viewtiful Joe]]'' series released from 2003 to 2005.<ref name=\"viewtiful joe\">{{cite video game | title = [[Viewtiful Joe]] | date = October 7, 2013 | scene=Closing credits, Voices | developer = [[Clover Studio]] | publisher = Capcom }}</ref> He provided the creature sounds for the ''[[Spore (2008 video game)|Spore]]'' video game which allows players to create and evolve their own creatures.<ref name=\"shortchanged\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-actors7-2009dec07-story.html#page=1|title=Video game voice actors worry they're getting shortchanged|date=December 7, 2009|work=[[Los Angeles Times|latimes.com]]|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"mix online\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.mixonline.com/news/films-tv/sfp-magical-world-spore/369211 |title=Mix magazine profile of Electronic Arts Maxis Spore game sound production for the EA videogame Spore audio in Mix magazine|work=[[Mix (magazine)|Mix]] | date=September 1, 2008 | first=Blair | last=Jackson | accessdate=September 15, 2015}}</ref> At San Diego Comic-Con 2008's opening night, he was a featured performer at the ''[[Video Games Live]]'' concert, where he voiced characters from ''[[Gears of War]]'' and other series.<ref name=\"video games live\">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2008-07-22/video-games-live-to-perform-with-the-san-diego-symphony-during-opening-night-of-comic-con|title=Video Games Live to Perform with the San Diego Symphony During Opening Night of Comic-Con|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> He provided voices for two [[Blizzard Entertainment]] characters \u2013 Murky, a baby [[murloc]] in ''[[Heroes of the Storm]],'' and [[Wrecking Ball (Overwatch)|Hammond]], a genetically engineered hamster in ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blizzardwatch.com/2019/01/29/live-look-inside-blizzards-voice-acting-dee-bradley-baker-bafta/|title=A live look inside Blizzard's voice acting with Dee Bradley Baker and BAFTA|date=2019-01-29|website=Blizzard Watch|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n<!-- current activity -->\nIn 2014, Baker continued participating in ''American Dad'', ''Gravity Falls'' and a fourth season of ''The Legend of Korra''. He voiced Dopey in the Disney XD series ''[[The 7D]]'';<ref name=\"disney examiner 7d\">{{cite web | url=http://disneyexaminer.com/2014/07/10/dee-bradley-baker-whistles-while-he-works-as-dopey-on-the-7d-show-and-app/ | title=Dee Bradley Baker Whistles While He Works as Dopey on \"The 7D\" | publisher=Storyteller Media | work=Disney Examiner | date=July 10, 2014 | last=Orenda | first=Tami}}</ref> and Fish, Wheels and Bucket in ''[[The Boxtrolls]]'' film,<ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\"/><ref name=\"boxtrolls dee\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.digitaltutors.com/dt-exclusive-interview-boxtrolls-voice-sound-artist-dee-baker/|title=DT Interviews \"Boxtrolls\" Voice and Sound Artist, Dee Baker|work=Digital-Tutors Blog|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> in which he was nominated for an Annie Award for voicing Fish.<ref name=\"annie award boxtrolls\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/nominees/|title=42nd Annual Annie Award Nominees|accessdate=December 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"focus features site\">{{cite web | url = http://www.focusfeatures.com/the_boxtrolls | title = The Boxtrolls \u2013 Movie Overview | work = Focus Features | publisher = NBC Universal | accessdate = September 2, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140922081827/http://www.focusfeatures.com/the_boxtrolls | archive-date = September 22, 2014 | url-status = dead }} \u2013 Cast & Crew</ref> In the ''[[Lego Batman 3: Beyond Gotham]]'' video game, he voiced [[Brainiac (character)|Brainiac]].<ref name=\"game informer troy and dee\">{{cite web | url =http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2014/08/02/lego-batman-39-s-troy-baker-on-more-last-of-us-and-dee-bradley-baker-on-left-4-dead.aspx | title = Lego Batman's Troy Baker On More Last Of Us And Dee Bradley Baker On Left 4 Dead | work = [[Game Informer]] | first=Kyle |last=Hilliard | date = August 2, 2014 }}</ref> He voiced George Clooney and his dog in \"[[Hot in Cleveland (season 5)#ep98|The Animated Episode]]\" of the TV Land series ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]''.<ref name=\"hot in cleveland\">{{cite episode | at=19:48 | url=http://www.tvland.com/episodes/y5mhtn/hot-in-cleveland-the-animated-episode-ep-516 | title=The Animated Episode | episodelink=Hot in Cleveland (season 5)#ep18 | series=Hot in Cleveland | serieslink=Hot in Cleveland | airdate=2014-07-30 | season=5 | number=18 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120202/http://www.tvland.com/episodes/y5mhtn/hot-in-cleveland-the-animated-episode-ep-516 | archivedate=October 6, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n<!-- voice acting -->\nBaker has appeared on various panels at Comic-Con and other conventions where he talks about voice acting in general.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voiceactingmastery.com/comic-con-panel-with-dee-bradley-baker-and-chris-borders|title=Comic Con Panel with Dee Bradley Baker and Chris Borders|work=Voice Acting Mastery: Become a Master Voice Actor in the World of Voice Over|date=July 24, 2011 | first=Crispin |last=Freeman | authorlink = Crispin Freeman|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref> He hosts a website where he answers frequently-asked questions about voice acting.<ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\"/> The site has been cited by fellow voice actors [[Steven Blum]] and [[Rob Paulsen]] as a valuable resource for getting into voice acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steveblumvoices.com/?page_id=279|title=How do I become a voice actor? | work = Steve Blum Voices | first=Steve |last=Blum | authorlink = Steven Blum | accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast| url= http://techjives.net/2012/07/20/050-yuri-lowenthal-and-tara-platt-on-talkin-toons-with-rob-paulsen-weekly-voice-acting-and-voice-over-tips/| title=050 \u2013 Yuri Lowenthal and Tara Platt on Talkin Toons with Rob Paulsen \u2013 Weekly Voice Acting and Voice Over Tips| work=Talkin Tools| publisher=Tech Jives Network| host=[[Rob Paulsen]]| date=July 20, 2012| time= 43}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBaker met his wife, Michelle, when they were doing children's theatre at the [[Colorado Springs Fine Arts Center]]. They were married in 1990 and have two daughters: Josie and Cora.<ref name=\"greeley tribune\"/><ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> They live in the Los Angeles area.<!-- see twitter --> Outside of voice acting, Baker enjoys photography,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deebakerphotography.com/about.html|title=Dee Baker Photography \u2013 About|work=Dee Baker Photography|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref> taking pictures of mostly small flowers and insects.<ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Dee Bradley Baker filmography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web | url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Dee-Bradley-Baker/ | title=Behind the Voice Actors \u2013 Dee Bradley Baker | work=Behind the Voice Actors | accessdate=February 3, 2017|postscript=. Check mark indicates BTVA has verified the entries using screenshots of credits and other confirmed sources.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n; Book references\n* {{cite book | ref={{harvid|Brooks & Marsh|2009}} | title = [[The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows 1946\u2013Present]] |edition=9th | author-first1=Tim |author-last1=Brooks | authorlink1 = Tim Brooks (television historian) | author-first2=Earle F. | author-last2=Marsh | isbn = 9780307483201 | publisher = Random House Publishing Group | year = 2009 }}\n* {{cite book | ref={{harvid|Terrace|2008}} | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YX_daEhlnbsC | title = Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010 | edition=2d | first=Vincent |last=Terrace | isbn = 9780786486410 | publisher = McFarland | year = 2008 }}\n* {{cite book | ref={{harvid|Perlmutter|2014}} | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aa0zAwAAQBAJ | title = America Toons In: A History of Television Animation | first =David |last=Perlmutter | publisher = McFarland | year = 2014 | isbn = 9781476614885 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.deebaker.com}}\n* {{Official website|http://iwanttobeavoiceactor.com|I Want To Be A Voice Actor}} \u2013 Baker's voice-over advice site.\n* {{IMDb name|0048389}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=341397|name=Dee Bradley Baker}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Dee Bradley}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Animal impersonators]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon people]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network people]]\n[[Category:Boettcher Scholars]]\n[[Category:American puppeteers]] <!-- puppeteer is from Olmec on Legends of the Hidden Temple -->\n[[Category:Colorado College alumni]]\n[[Category:Game show announcers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Colorado]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Indiana]]\n[[Category:People from Greeley, Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Bloomington, Indiana]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American voice actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Dee Bradley Baker\n|image = Dee Bradley Baker by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n|caption = Baker at [[WonderCon|WonderCon 2016]]\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|8|31}}  \n|birth_place = [[Bloomington, Indiana]], U.S.\n|home_town = [[Greeley, Colorado]], U.S.\n|residence = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S. <!-- Twitter indicates Los Angeles -->\n|alma_mater = [[Colorado College]]\n| agent = Cynthia McLean<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=CRS20070307.2.10.3|title=Talent Agent Lectures for Mary Pickford Series | volume = 93 | number = 3| newspaper = Corsair Newspaper \u2013 [[Santa Monica College]] | first=Barbara |last=Szabo | date = March 7, 2007 | via= California Digital Newspaper Collection |accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\">{{cite web | url = http://www.toonzone.net/2014/09/toonzone-interviews-dee-bradley-baker-steve-blum-speak-boxtroll/ | title = Toonzone Interviews Dee Bradley Baker & Steve Blum on How to Speak Boxtroll | date = September 25, 2014 | work = Toonzone | first = Ed |last=Liu }}</ref>\n|occupation = Voice actor\n| years_active = 1993\u2013present <!-- Legends of the Hidden Temple was his first major TV role -->\n|other_names =\n| spouse= {{marriage|Michelle Baker|1990}}\n| children = 2\n|URL = {{URL|http://www.deebaker.com}}\n}}\n'''Dee Bradley Baker''' (born August 31, 1962)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.wired.com/geekdad/2011/08/happy-birthday-dee-bradley-baker-2/|title=Happy Birthday, Dee Bradley Baker!|work=GeekDad|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired.com]] | date=August 31, 2011 | accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><!-- confirms only month and day --><ref name=\"sentinel 1991\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1991-08-30/news/9108300714_1_dee-baker-fortner-side-story|title=Baker Fits The Bill In 'West Side Story'|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publication-date=August 30, 1991|first= Laurie |last=Whitmore|quote= At the age of 28, Baker is among the lucky minority of entertainers who can call themselves working actors}}</ref><!-- confirms year --> is an American [[Voice acting|voice actor]]. His major roles, many of which feature his vocalizations of animals, include animated series such as ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'', ''[[American Dad!]]'', ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'', ''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]'', ''[[Gravity Falls]]'', ''[[Steven Universe]]'', ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'',  ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'', ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', ''[[Ben 10]]'', ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'' and ''[[The 7D]]'', live action series such as ''[[Legends of the Hidden Temple]]'' and ''[[Shop 'til You Drop]]'', films such as ''[[The Boxtrolls]]'' and ''[[Space Jam]]'' and video games such as ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'', ''[[Gears of War]]'', ''[[Viewtiful Joe (series)|Viewtiful Joe]]'', ''[[Spore (2008 video game)|Spore]]'', and ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nBaker was born in [[Bloomington, Indiana]] to Buddy and Nancy Baker,<ref name=\"nancy obit\">{{cite web|url=https://obittree.com/obituary/us/colorado/fort-collins/allnutt-funeral-service/nancy-baker/898848/|title=Nancy Ann Baker Obituary \u2013 December 21, 1935 - April 24, 2007 |author=|date=|work=ObitTree|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"greeley tribune\">{{cite web|url=https://www.greeleytribune.com/news/vocal-vocation-greeley-native-makes-a-living-voicing-characters-in-films-tv-shows/|title=Vocal vocation: Greeley native makes a living voicing characters in films, TV shows|first=Dan | last=England | date=February 14, 2007 | work=Greeley Tribune | access-date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> and grew up in [[Greeley, Colorado]].<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> He started performing at age nine and steadily worked in musicals, operas, plays and stand-up. As a child he was a fan of ''[[Star Trek]]'', ''[[Star Wars]]'', [[Frank Zappa]] and the ''[[Planet of the Apes]]'', and also liked insects, arthropods and dinosaurs.<ref name=\"VO studio interview\">{{cite video | title = VO Studio: Dee Baker | author = Zev Suissa | work = VO Studio | date = April 11, 2013 }}</ref> He graduated from [[University Charter Schools (Colorado)|University High School]] in 1981<ref name=\"greeley tribune\"/> and received a [[Boettcher Scholarship]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.boettcherfoundation.org/home/scholarships/graduated-scholars/featured-scholar-profiles | title = Featured Scholar Profiles \u2013 Under Water is a Good Thing | work = [[Boettcher Foundation]] | accessdate=September 17, 2014 }}</ref> \n\nHe attended [[Colorado College]] in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado]], where he studied philosophy, biology, fine arts and German, the last of which he studied overseas for a year at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]].<ref name=\"emily interview\">{{cite video | url = http://www.comicmix.com/2013/08/13/emily-s-whitten-dee-bradley-baker-is-an-animal/ | title = Emily S. Whitten: Dee Bradley Baker is an Animal! | work = ComicMix | date = August 11, 2013 | first = Emily S. |last=Whitten }} \u2013 includes YouTube interview</ref> He was involved in local theater productions and singing groups. After graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in philosophy, he was involved in many community theatre projects, including a sketch movie that aired on local public television.<ref name=\"honorary bio\">{{cite web | url = http://www.coloradocollege.edu/dotAsset/247c7215-4c99-48d2-97f1-250384649fda.pdf |title = Dee Bradley Baker '86 | work = [[Colorado College]] | accessdate = September 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Dee Bradley Baker by Gage Skidmore 3.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Baker at the 2010 [[San Diego Comic Con]]]]\nBaker moved to Orlando in 1989 to work on an improv sketch comedy show titled \"The Anacomical Players\" at [[EPCOT Center]]'s [[Wonders of Life]] pavilion and joined various projects for Disney and Universal Studios.<ref name=\"sentinel 1991\"/><ref name=\"honorary bio\"/><ref name=\"D23\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N7XbceE2LTY|title=Full Voices of the Disney Theme Parks presentation from D23 Expo 2011|date=August 27, 2011|accessdate=September 19, 2012|format=YouTube|work=Attractions Magazine}} \u2013 4 minutes in for Pirates, 15 minutes in for Boba Fett <!-- boba fett self-claim during panel interview--></ref> His first major experience on national television was on the Nickelodeon game show ''[[Legends of the Hidden Temple]]'', where he was not only the announcer, but also the giant talking rock-god Olmec.<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/><ref name=\"twitter legends\">{{cite tweet| user = deebradleybaker| number = 338294639410941952 <!-- https://twitter.com/deebradleybaker/status/338294639410941952 -->| title = \"''Legends of the Hidden Temple'' was my 1st show. Forever a fan favorite! RT @The90sLife: Olmec #beststatuesofthe90s\"| author = Dee Bradley Baker| date = May 25, 2013| accessdate = December 13, 2014}}</ref> He portrayed Olmec with a \"big, booming, loud, god-like voice\". During parts of the show, he would narrate a legend, and then ask the kid contestants related trivia questions. The show lasted three seasons and 120 episodes. When host [[Kirk Fogg]] moved to Los Angeles, he was encouraged to move there as well.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.buzzfeed.com/jaimieetkin/legends-of-the-hidden-temple-kirk-fogg-olmec | title = The Legend Of \"Legends Of The Hidden Temple,\" As Told By Kirk Fogg and Olmec | work = [[BuzzFeed]] | first=Jamie | last=Etkin | date = September 11, 2013 }}</ref> In 2016, he and Fogg reprised their roles for a [[Legends of the Hidden Temple (film)|live action television movie adaptation]] of the show.<ref name=\"variety legends 2016\">{{cite web |author=McClendon, Lamarco |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/tv-news-legends-of-the-hidden-temple-movie-dee-bradley-baker-rosewood-brian-austin-green-1201801425/ |title=TV News Roundup: 'Legends of the Hidden Temple' Revival Brings Back Original Olmec; Brian Austin Green Joins 'Rosewood' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBaker moved to Southern California in time for the [[1994 Northridge earthquake]]. He got involved in voice-over work; his first major character was Cow & Chicken's dad in the ''[[Cow & Chicken]]'' and ''[[I Am Weasel]]'' cartoons.<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> His first feature film voice-over was on the basketball/Looney Tunes-themed movie ''[[Space Jam]]'' where he voiced [[Daffy Duck]], [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Taz]] and [[Bully for Bugs|Toro]].<ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> He did voice work for various episodic and recurring cartoon characters on ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]'',<ref name=\"jonny quest\">{{cite AV media | at=Closing credits | title=Future Rage | series=The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest | serieslink=The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest | season=1 | number=24}}</ref> ''[[Johnny Bravo]]'', ''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]'',<ref name=\"dexter3-1\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=Streaky Clean/A Dad Cartoon/Sole Brother | date=2001 | series=Dexter's Laboratory | serieslink=Dexter's Laboratory | season=3 | number=1}}</ref> ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]''<ref name=\"brooks-1285\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=1285}}</ref> and ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]''.<ref name=\"powerpuff 4-4\">{{cite episode | episode=4 | title=Him Diddle Riddle | series=The Powerpuff Girls | serieslink=The Powerpuff Girls | airdate=2002-06-21 | season=4}}</ref> He voiced starring characters Og in ''[[Mike, Lu & Og]]''<ref name=\"brooks-895\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=895}}</ref> and [[Bagheera]] in the second season of ''[[Jungle Cubs]]''.<ref name=\"terrace-549\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=549}}</ref> In 2001, he added voice roles for Sanjay, Binky and other characters for ''[[The Fairly OddParents]]''<ref name=\"terrace-322\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=322}}</ref><ref name=\"btva\"/> and co-starred as Mandy's father on ''[[Billy and Mandy]]''.<ref name=\"terrace-418\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=418}}</ref><ref name=\"btva\"/> He had a lead role as [[Codename: Kids Next Door#Kids Next Door|Numbuh 4]] in ''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]''.<ref name=\"brooks-268\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=268}}</ref> On the live action front, he became the co-host and announcer for the game show ''[[Shop 'til You Drop]]'' which spanned several hundred episodes when it resumed broadcasting on the [[Television networks preceding Freeform|Family Channel]] and on the [[Ion Television#Pax TV (1998\u20132005)|Pax television network]], until a series retool in 2003; it was produced by Stone Stanley Entertainment, which had earlier co-produced ''Legends of the Hidden Temple''.<ref name=\"brooks-1230\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|pp=1230\u20131231}}</ref> He also had a recurring role as Phil Berg in the Nickelodeon sitcom series ''[[The Journey of Allen Strange]]'' where he plays a crazed journalist who tries to expose Allen's identity as a space alien.<ref name=\"brooks-717\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=717}}</ref>\n\n<!-- animal characters -->\nStarting with gigs on ''[[The Wild Thornberrys]]'', he voiced an assortment of animal characters, which would become one of his specialties.<ref name=\"btva\"/> He voiced Pig George in the live action animal film ''[[My Brother the Pig]]''.<ref name=\"my brother the pig movie\">{{cite video| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WfrO3fLP8zc | format=YouTube | author = [[FilmRise|FilmRise movies]] | title = My Brother the Pig \u2013 Starring Scarlett Johansson \u2013 Full Movie | at=1:28:48 }}</ref> Baker has also been involved with television shows for younger children including: ''[[Dora the Explorer]]'' where he provided animal sounds;<ref name=\"dora\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=Boots Cuddly Dinosaur | series=Dora the Explorer | serieslink=Dora the Explorer}}</ref> ''[[Mickey Mouse Clubhouse]]'' where he voices [[Mickey Mouse Clubhouse#Boo Boo Chicken|Boo Boo Chicken]];<ref name=\"mmc 5-1\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=Mickey Goes Fishing | series=Mickey Mouse Clubhouse | serieslink=Mickey Mouse Clubhouse | season=1 | number=5}}</ref> ''[[Curious George (TV series)|Curious George]]'' where he voices Gnocchi;<ref name=\"gnocchi\">{{cite episode | at=Closing credits | title=No Knowing Gnocchi / Here Comes the Tide | series=Curious George | serieslink=Curious George (TV series) | season=6 | number=10}}</ref> ''[[My Friends Tigger & Pooh]]'' where he voices [[List of Winnie-the-Pooh characters#Buster|Buster]] the dog<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdizzy.com/frankenweenie.html|title=Frankenweenie Blu-ray 3D, Blu-ray & DVD Review | work = DVDizzy.com |accessdate=September 30, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Jake and the Neverland Pirates]]'' (airing on [[Disney Junior]]) where he voices Tick-Tock the crocodile.<ref name=\"btva\"/> In ''[[Avatar: The Last Airbender]]'' where he voiced the creatures [[Appa (character)|Appa]] and [[Momo (Avatar: The Last Airbender)|Momo]]<ref name=\"brooks-88\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=88}}</ref> and would soon voice many other creatures in the series as well as its sequel, ''[[The Legend of Korra]]'', where he voices Naga, Pabu and Oogi. He voiced in the ''[[American Dragon: Jake Long]]''<ref name=\"jake long\">{{cite web | url=http://www.jeffgoode.com/tv/americandragon/02season/219.htm | title=American Dragon: Jake Long \u2013 episode 219 \u2013 \"A Ghost Story\" \u2013 by Chris Nee | work=Jeff Goode Official Website | accessdate=October 4, 2014 | last=Goode | first=Jeff | authorlink=Jeff Goode}}</ref> and ''[[Ben 10]]'' series, the latter of which he voiced many alien creatures such as [[List of Ben 10 aliens#Stinkfly|Stinkfly]] and [[Wildmutt]], as well as some of the transformations.<ref name=\"btva\" /><ref name=\"brooks-123\">{{Harvnb|Brooks & Marsh|2009|p=123}}</ref> He also voiced in the ''Ben 10'' sequels such as ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]'',<ref name=\"terrace-89\">{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=89}}</ref> ''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]'' and ''[[Ben 10: Omniverse]]'', as well as its live-action adaptation.<ref name=\"btva\"/><ref name=\"formspring\">{{cite news | url=http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/340540854995280906 | title=Will Humungousaur, Cannonbolt, Spidermonkey be voiced by Dee Bradley Baker in Omniverse, or will it be by someone else? | work=[[Formspring]] | last=Wyatt | first=Derrick J. | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412185629/http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/340540854995280906 | archivedate=April 12, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"formspring2\">{{cite web | url=http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/349221639273073039 | title=What made everyone decide to have a variety of voice actors voicing the Ben 10 aliens? (Dee Bradley Baker voicing every alien besides Rath was the dumbest idea in the universe...) | last=Wyatt | first=Derrick J. | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412185630/http://www.formspring.me/DerrickJWyatt/q/349221639273073039 | archivedate=April 12, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Derrick J. Wyatt, who was the art director for ''Omniverse'', noted that they had to allow other voice actors to do some of the aliens in the later series because Baker was doing almost all of them and some of the characters were putting a strain on his throat.<ref name=\"formspring2\"/> Outside of television, he provided the voice of [[Captain Jack Sparrow]]'s talking parrot in the refurbished ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' rides at Disneyland and the [[Magic Kingdom]].<ref name=\"D23\"/><ref name=\"dis unplugged\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disunplugged.com/2010/05/21/star-wars-weekends-send-in-the-clones/|title=Star Wars Weekends: Send In The Clones! - The DIS Unplugged Disney Podcast|author=|date=|website=www.disunplugged.com|accessdate=November 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!--- need more details on how he portrays perry -->\nIn 2007, Baker got the role of [[Perry the Platypus]] in the Disney series ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]''. At the San Diego Comic-Con 2013 panel, Baker mentioned that when he auditioned, he was asked to provide three different creature sounds, regardless of whether it actually sounded like a platypus, of which one was selected as Perry's characteristic sound.<ref name=\"comic-con 2013 phineas and ferb\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2-adkax_QLA|title=Full Phineas and Ferb panel at San Diego Comic-Con 2013 including Marvel, Star Wars|format=YouTube|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Perry has become a [[breakout character]] for the series,<ref name=\"star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118011690.html?categoryId=1050&cs=1|title='Phineas' star Perry makes mark on auds|author=Littleton, Cynthia|date=November 20, 2009|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 26, 2009}}</ref> with Baker appearing at multiple Comic-Con panels for the show.<ref name=\"comic-con 2013 phineas and ferb\"/> In 2014, Perry was nominated for a [[Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Award]] for Best Animal Sidekick. Coincidentally, another one of Baker's voiced characters, Waddles the pet pig in ''[[Gravity Falls]]'', was nominated for the same category.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/kids_choice_awards_2014_full_winners_list-2014-03 | title = Kids' Choice Awards 2014 Full Winners List | work = [[Zap2It]] | first=Laurel | last=Brown | date = March 20, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n<!-- regular animation more details regarding klaus -->\nBaker would continue to do regular voice-over roles. In 2005, he landed a role as [[Klaus Heissler]], an Olympic ski jumper from Germany who was [[Body swap|body-swapped]] into a goldfish, in the primetime cartoon sitcom ''[[American Dad!]]'',<ref name=\"ovguide1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ovguide.com/roger-9202a8c04000641f80000000008d8419 | title=Roger Video &#124; Movie Clips & Character Interview | publisher=Ovguide.com | accessdate=April 9, 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521175723/http://www.ovguide.com/roger-9202a8c04000641f80000000008d8419 | archivedate=May 21, 2013 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"washingtonpost1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/therootdc/post/american-dad-one-of-the-most-sophisticated-mainstream-shows-on-african-american-culture/2012/10/08/e8374cba-051d-11e2-91e7-2962c74e7738_blog.html | title='American Dad': One of the most sophisticated mainstream shows on African American culture \u2013 The Root DC Live | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=October 8, 2012 | accessdate=April 1, 2013 | last=McEwen | first=Lauren}}</ref> which has run over eleven seasons on Fox and TBS. In an interview with Pop Break, Baker said that he liked playing Klaus because he loves the German language, the part was well written, and it is light duty on his voice. He compared the [[Read-through|table reads]] to being on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]''.<ref name=\"pop break\">{{cite web | url=http://pop-break.com/2014/11/03/american-dad-interview-series-baker-macfarlane/ | title=American Dad Interview Series: Dee Bradley Baker & Rachael MacFarlane | date=November 3, 2014 | work = Pop-Break.com | first=Luke | last=Kalamar }}</ref> He participated in ''American Dad'' panels at [[San Diego Comic-Con International|San Diego Comic-Con]] 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2010/06/comiccon-2010.html|title='Caprica' will be there, 'Game of Thrones' will not: The Comic-Con lineup|publisher=|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/06/13/glee-cast-and-creators-return-to-comic-con-2012-in-star-studded-panel-saturday-july-14/137885/|title='Glee' Cast and Creators Return to Comic-Con 2012 in Star-Studded Panel Saturday, July 14 - Ratings - TVbytheNumbers.Zap2it.com|work=TVbytheNumbers|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> and 2014;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comic-con.org/cci/saturday|title=Comic-Con 2014 Saturday Programs|work=Comic-Con International: San Diego|accessdate=October 18, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023175201/http://www.comic-con.org/cci/saturday | archivedate=October 23, 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> and the [[New York Comic-Con]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/american-dad-article-1.1967982|title=New York Comic Con 2014: 'American Dad's' move to TBS brings strong story with more dirty words to new season|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=October 18, 2014}}</ref> His voicing of council member Tarrlok in ''Korra'' garnered a nomination for the Behind the Voice Actors (BTVA) Voice Acting Award in 2012.<ref name=\"about basile\">{{cite web | url=http://animatedtv.about.com/od/clonewars/p/Dee-Bradley-Baker.htm | title=Dee Bradley Baker | work=Animated TV at About.com | accessdate=September 22, 2014 | last=Basile | first=Nancy | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924044959/http://animatedtv.about.com/od/clonewars/p/Dee-Bradley-Baker.htm | archivedate=September 24, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Terrace|2008|p=832}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Perlmutter|2014|p=367}}</ref><ref name=\"btva korra\">{{cite web | url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/btva-awards/2012/television/ | title=2012 Annual BTVA Voice Acting Awards | work=Behind the Voice Actors | accessdate=September 22, 2014}}</ref> In addition to television shows, Baker voiced characters in many animated and live action animation films, including some of the classic ghost monsters in ''[[Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed]]'',<ref name=\"scooby movie 2\">{{cite web | url = https://www.allmovie.com/movie/scooby-doo-2-monsters-unleashed-v286521/cast-crew | title = Scooby-Doo 2: Monsters Unleashed (2004) \u2013 Cast and Crew | work = AllMovie | accessdate=September 23, 2014 }}</ref> Maurice in ''[[Happy Feet]]'',<ref name=\"btva\"/> He had roles in the ''[[Scooby-Doo! Mystery Incorporated]]'' TV series and its direct-to-video releases.<ref name=\"btva\"/>\n\n<!--- star wars: also need more details on the troopers --->\nBaker was involved in the ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' film released in 2008 and [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|its television series]] afterwards which ran for six seasons. He provided the voices for not only the characters [[Captain Rex]] and Commander Cody, but also all the supporting [[Clone Troopers]],<ref name=\"about basile\"/><ref name=\"awn clones\">{{cite web | url=http://www.awn.com/news/dee-bradley-baker-discusses-voicing-clones-star-wars-clone-wars | title=Dee Bradley Baker Discusses Voicing The Clones in Star Wars: The Clone Wars | work=Animation World Magazine | date=October 23, 2008 | last=Moody | first=Annemarie}}</ref><ref name=\"annie awards clones\">{{cite web | url=http://annieawards.org/39th-annie-awards | title=39th Annie Awards | work=[[Annie Awards]] | accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"voicing an army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonzone.net/2011/09/new-voicing-an-army-bts-clip-from-star-wars-the-clone-wars/|title=New \"Voicing an Army\" BTS Clip from \"Star Wars: The Clone Wars\"|work=Toon Zone News}}</ref><ref name=\"ign rex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2011/09/06/star-wars-the-clone-wars-whats-next-for-rex|title=Star Wars: The Clone Wars - What's Next for Rex?|work=IGN|date=September 6, 2011|first=Eric|last=Goldman}}</ref> the last of which he received an [[Annie Award]] nomination for Voice Acting in a Television Production in 2012.<ref name=\"annie awards clones\"/> He reprised the role of Captain Rex in ''[[Star Wars Rebels]]'', beginning with its second season. He also provided the voice of [[Boba Fett]] for ''[[Star Tours \u2013 The Adventures Continue]]''.<ref name=\"D23\"/> In the 2011 ''[[Family Guy]]'' episode \"[[It's a Trap!]]\", a parody of the ''Star Wars'' film ''[[Return of the Jedi]]'', he voiced Klaus as [[Admiral Ackbar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Manco |first=Emanuele |title=Family Guy: It's a Trap |work=Fantasy Magazine |date=December 24, 2010 |url=http://www.fantasymagazine.it/notizie/13738/family-guy-it-s-a-trap/ |language=Italian |accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<!-- video games -->\nIn the video game world, Baker reprised his roles in Cartoon Network and Nickelodeon's multitude of show-related game releases. He also voiced Gravemind in ''[[Halo 2]]'' and ''[[Halo 3]],''<ref name=\"btva\"/> and the title character Joe in the ''[[Viewtiful Joe (series)|Viewtiful Joe]]'' series released from 2003 to 2005.<ref name=\"viewtiful joe\">{{cite video game | title = [[Viewtiful Joe]] | date = October 7, 2013 | scene=Closing credits, Voices | developer = [[Clover Studio]] | publisher = Capcom }}</ref> He provided the creature sounds for the ''[[Spore (2008 video game)|Spore]]'' video game which allows players to create and evolve their own creatures.<ref name=\"shortchanged\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-ct-actors7-2009dec07-story.html#page=1|title=Video game voice actors worry they're getting shortchanged|date=December 7, 2009|work=[[Los Angeles Times|latimes.com]]|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"mix online\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.mixonline.com/news/films-tv/sfp-magical-world-spore/369211 |title=Mix magazine profile of Electronic Arts Maxis Spore game sound production for the EA videogame Spore audio in Mix magazine|work=[[Mix (magazine)|Mix]] | date=September 1, 2008 | first=Blair | last=Jackson | accessdate=September 15, 2015}}</ref> At San Diego Comic-Con 2008's opening night, he was a featured performer at the ''[[Video Games Live]]'' concert, where he voiced characters from ''[[Gears of War]]'' and other series.<ref name=\"video games live\">{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2008-07-22/video-games-live-to-perform-with-the-san-diego-symphony-during-opening-night-of-comic-con|title=Video Games Live to Perform with the San Diego Symphony During Opening Night of Comic-Con|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> He provided voices for two [[Blizzard Entertainment]] characters \u2013 Murky, a baby [[murloc]] in ''[[Heroes of the Storm]],'' and [[Wrecking Ball (Overwatch)|Hammond]], a genetically engineered hamster in ''[[Overwatch (video game)|Overwatch]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blizzardwatch.com/2019/01/29/live-look-inside-blizzards-voice-acting-dee-bradley-baker-bafta/|title=A live look inside Blizzard's voice acting with Dee Bradley Baker and BAFTA|date=2019-01-29|website=Blizzard Watch|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\n<!-- current activity -->\nIn 2014, Baker continued participating in ''American Dad'', ''Gravity Falls'' and a fourth season of ''The Legend of Korra''. He voiced Dopey in the Disney XD series ''[[The 7D]]'';<ref name=\"disney examiner 7d\">{{cite web | url=http://disneyexaminer.com/2014/07/10/dee-bradley-baker-whistles-while-he-works-as-dopey-on-the-7d-show-and-app/ | title=Dee Bradley Baker Whistles While He Works as Dopey on \"The 7D\" | publisher=Storyteller Media | work=Disney Examiner | date=July 10, 2014 | last=Orenda | first=Tami}}</ref> and Fish, Wheels and Bucket in ''[[The Boxtrolls]]'' film,<ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\"/><ref name=\"boxtrolls dee\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.digitaltutors.com/dt-exclusive-interview-boxtrolls-voice-sound-artist-dee-baker/|title=DT Interviews \"Boxtrolls\" Voice and Sound Artist, Dee Baker|work=Digital-Tutors Blog|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref> in which he was nominated for an Annie Award for voicing Fish.<ref name=\"annie award boxtrolls\">{{cite web|url=http://annieawards.org/nominees/|title=42nd Annual Annie Award Nominees|accessdate=December 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"focus features site\">{{cite web | url = http://www.focusfeatures.com/the_boxtrolls | title = The Boxtrolls \u2013 Movie Overview | work = Focus Features | publisher = NBC Universal | accessdate = September 2, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140922081827/http://www.focusfeatures.com/the_boxtrolls | archive-date = September 22, 2014 | url-status = dead }} \u2013 Cast & Crew</ref> In the ''[[Lego Batman 3: Beyond Gotham]]'' video game, he voiced [[Brainiac (character)|Brainiac]].<ref name=\"game informer troy and dee\">{{cite web | url =http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2014/08/02/lego-batman-39-s-troy-baker-on-more-last-of-us-and-dee-bradley-baker-on-left-4-dead.aspx | title = Lego Batman's Troy Baker On More Last Of Us And Dee Bradley Baker On Left 4 Dead | work = [[Game Informer]] | first=Kyle |last=Hilliard | date = August 2, 2014 }}</ref> He voiced George Clooney and his dog in \"[[Hot in Cleveland (season 5)#ep98|The Animated Episode]]\" of the TV Land series ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]''.<ref name=\"hot in cleveland\">{{cite episode | at=19:48 | url=http://www.tvland.com/episodes/y5mhtn/hot-in-cleveland-the-animated-episode-ep-516 | title=The Animated Episode | episodelink=Hot in Cleveland (season 5)#ep18 | series=Hot in Cleveland | serieslink=Hot in Cleveland | airdate=2014-07-30 | season=5 | number=18 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006120202/http://www.tvland.com/episodes/y5mhtn/hot-in-cleveland-the-animated-episode-ep-516 | archivedate=October 6, 2014 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n<!-- voice acting -->\nBaker has appeared on various panels at Comic-Con and other conventions where he talks about voice acting in general.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voiceactingmastery.com/comic-con-panel-with-dee-bradley-baker-and-chris-borders|title=Comic Con Panel with Dee Bradley Baker and Chris Borders|work=Voice Acting Mastery: Become a Master Voice Actor in the World of Voice Over|date=July 24, 2011 | first=Crispin |last=Freeman | authorlink = Crispin Freeman|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref> He hosts a website where he answers frequently-asked questions about voice acting.<ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\"/> The site has been cited by fellow voice actors [[Steven Blum]] and [[Rob Paulsen]] as a valuable resource for getting into voice acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steveblumvoices.com/?page_id=279|title=How do I become a voice actor? | work = Steve Blum Voices | first=Steve |last=Blum | authorlink = Steven Blum | accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite podcast| url= http://techjives.net/2012/07/20/050-yuri-lowenthal-and-tara-platt-on-talkin-toons-with-rob-paulsen-weekly-voice-acting-and-voice-over-tips/| title=050 \u2013 Yuri Lowenthal and Tara Platt on Talkin Toons with Rob Paulsen \u2013 Weekly Voice Acting and Voice Over Tips| work=Talkin Tools| publisher=Tech Jives Network| host=[[Rob Paulsen]]| date=July 20, 2012| time= 43}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBaker met his wife, Michelle, when they were doing children's theatre at the [[Colorado Springs Fine Arts Center]]. They were married in 1990 and have two daughters: Josie and Cora.<ref name=\"greeley tribune\"/><ref name=\"honorary bio\"/> They live in the Los Angeles area.<!-- see twitter --> Outside of voice acting, Baker enjoys photography,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deebakerphotography.com/about.html|title=Dee Baker Photography \u2013 About|work=Dee Baker Photography|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref> taking pictures of mostly small flowers and insects.<ref name=\"boxtrolls dee blum\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Dee Bradley Baker filmography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web | url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Dee-Bradley-Baker/ | title=Behind the Voice Actors \u2013 Dee Bradley Baker | work=Behind the Voice Actors | accessdate=February 3, 2017|postscript=. Check mark indicates BTVA has verified the entries using screenshots of credits and other confirmed sources.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n; Book references\n* {{cite book | ref={{harvid|Brooks & Marsh|2009}} | title = [[The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network and Cable TV Shows 1946\u2013Present]] |edition=9th | author-first1=Tim |author-last1=Brooks | authorlink1 = Tim Brooks (television historian) | author-first2=Earle F. | author-last2=Marsh | isbn = 9780307483201 | publisher = Random House Publishing Group | year = 2009 }}\n* {{cite book | ref={{harvid|Terrace|2008}} | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=YX_daEhlnbsC | title = Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010 | edition=2d | first=Vincent |last=Terrace | isbn = 9780786486410 | publisher = McFarland | year = 2008 }}\n* {{cite book | ref={{harvid|Perlmutter|2014}} | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=aa0zAwAAQBAJ | title = America Toons In: A History of Television Animation | first =David |last=Perlmutter | publisher = McFarland | year = 2014 | isbn = 9781476614885 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.deebaker.com}}\n* {{Official website|http://iwanttobeavoiceactor.com|I Want To Be A Voice Actor}} \u2013 Baker's voice-over advice site.\n* {{IMDb name|0048389}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=341397|name=Dee Bradley Baker}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Dee Bradley}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male video game actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Animal impersonators]]\n[[Category:Nickelodeon people]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network people]]\n[[Category:Boettcher Scholars]]\n[[Category:American puppeteers]] <!-- puppeteer is from Olmec on Legends of the Hidden Temple -->\n[[Category:Colorado College alumni]]\n[[Category:Game show announcers]]\n