le=\"color:#0000f1\">11 April 2020</span></sup>\n\n==First team honours==\n[[File:League Two Playoff Trophy 2008.jpg|250px|thumb|The [[Football League Two|League Two]] play-off trophy]]\nHonours are correct as of the end of the 2018\u201319 season.<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n\n===Football League===\n\n*[[Football League One|Football League Second Division/Football League One]] \u2013 Tier 3\n**Runners Up: [[1996-97 Football League Second Division|1996\u201397]]\n**Playoff Runners Up: [[1991-92 Football League|1991\u201392]], [[1993-94 Football League|1993\u201394]]\n*[[Football League Third Division North]]\n**Champions: [[1921\u201322 Football League Third Division North|1921\u201322]], [[1936\u201337 Football League Third Division North|1936\u201337]]\n**Runners Up: [[1928-29 Football League Third Division North|1928\u201329]], [[1929\u201330 Football League Third Division North|1929\u201330]]\n*[[Football League Two|Football League Fourth Division/Football League Two]] \u2013 Tier 4\n**Champions: [[1966\u201367 Football League Fourth Division|1966\u201367]]\n**Runners Up: [[1990-91 Football League Fourth Division|1990\u201391]]\n**Play-Off Winners: [[2007\u201308 Football League Two|2007\u201308]]\n*Division Three (North) Challenge Cup\n**Winners: [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]]\n*[[Football League Trophy]]\n**Runners Up: [[1991-92 Football League Trophy|1991\u201392]], [[1992-93 Football League Trophy|1992\u201393]]\n\n===Other competitions===\n*[[National League North]] \u2013 Tier 6\n**Champions: [[2018\u201319 National League|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Lancashire League (football)|Lancashire League]]\n**Champions: 1899\u20131900\n*[[Lancashire Combination]]\n**Champions: 1904\u201305\n*[[Manchester Senior Cup]]\n**Winners: 1897\u201398, 1898\u201399, 1914\u201315, 1922\u201323\n*Cheshire Medal Winners:\n**1922\u201323, 1924\u201325, 1928\u201329, 1929\u201330, 1930\u201331\n*Cheshire Bowl Winners:\n**1933\u201334, 1948\u201349, 1952\u201353, 1955\u201356, 1956\u201357,1958\u201359, 1960\u201361, 1962\u201363\n*Cheshire Friendly Trophy Winners:\n**1965\u201366, 1966\u201367\n*[[Cheshire Premier Cup]]\n**Winners: 1969\u201370, 1970\u201371, 2010\u201311\n*[[Cheshire Senior Cup]]\n**Winners: 1905\u201306, 1946\u201347, 1948\u201349, 1965\u201366, 2015\u201316\n\n==Club records and statistics==\n\n===Team records===\n*Biggest home win: 13\u20130 vs. Halifax Town, 6 January 1934, also a [[Football League]] record<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Football League Matches: Arsenal Only Draw, Record Scoring by Stockport|work=The Manchester Guardian|date=8 January 1934|page=3}}</ref>\n*Biggest home defeat: 0\u20136, twice, most recently 24 April 2010 vs. [[Huddersfield Town F.C|Huddersfield Town]]<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Biggest away win: 7\u20131 at [[Bradford City F.C.|Bradford City]], 18 September 1965<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Biggest away defeat: 0\u20139, vs. [[Everton F.C.|Everton Reserves]], 9 December 1893<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Consecutive wins: 9, [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]]<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Consecutive away wins: 8, [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref name=\"Stockport boss has a young vision\">{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/7305219.stm | title=Stockport boss has a young vision| publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 March 2008|last=Oliver|first=Pete| accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n*Consecutive wins without conceding a goal: 9, [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]], also a [[Football League]] record<ref name=\"Programmes\"/><ref name=\"Stockport boss has a young vision\" /><ref name=\"FL record\">{{cite news |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/sport/story/0,,2026082,00.html |title=Leeds deeper in gloom as Nicholls says he wants away |accessdate=15 April 2012 |date=4 March 2007|last=Tomas|first=Jason|location=London|work=The Observer}}</ref>\n*Consecutive defeats: 12, [[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Consecutive games scored in: 30, [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Consecutive League games scored in: 26, [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Highest attendance: 27,833 vs. [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], FA Cup Fifth Round, 11 February 1950<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Highest league attendance: 24,473 vs. Oldham Athletic, Third Division North, 20 October 1951\n*Highest attendance (all-seated): 10,273 vs. Leeds United, 28 December 2008<ref name=\"Programmes\"/>\n*Lowest attendance: 812 vs. Barrow, 19 November 2013<ref name=\"FA Trophy replay: Stockport County 2 Barrow 3\">{{cite news |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/match-reports/fa-trophy-replay-stockport-county-6323773 |title=FA Trophy replay: Stockport County 2 Barrow 3|accessdate=16 September 2014 |date=20 November 2013|last=Browne|first=Gavin|location=Manchester|work=Manchester Evening News}}</ref>\n*Longest match: 3 hours 23 minutes vs. [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]], 30 March 1946, also a world record<ref name=\"Burnton-29Mar2018\"/>\n*Lowest number of paying spectators: 13 vs. [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] (at [[Old Trafford (football ground)|Old Trafford]], 7 May 1921) also a [[Football League]] record.{{Ref|TCCnote2|2}} \n\n===Player records===\n*Most goals (season): 46 League by Alf Lythgoe, [[1933\u201334 in English football|1933\u201334]]<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n*Most goals (career): 132 by [[Jack Connor (footballer born 1919)|Jack Connor]] (1951\u20131956)<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n*Fastest League Goal (Starting XI): 13 seconds, [[Dominic Blizzard]] vs. [[Hereford United F.C.|Hereford United]] 31 January 2009<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Fastest League Goal (Substitute): 21 seconds, Bohan Dixon vs. [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]]  6 January 2018<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Most appearances (career): 555 Andy Thorpe (1978\u20131986, 1988\u20131992)<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Nelson|first=Guy|title=Legends of Stockport County FC|publisher=At Heart|year=2008|isbn=9781845471958|location=Altrincham|pages=61}}</ref>\n*Most international appearances (caps) \u2013 9 [[Jarkko Wiss]], Finland (2000\u20132002)<ref name=\"Records\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Nelson|first=Guy|title=Legends of Stockport County FC|publisher=At Heart|year=2008|isbn=9781845471958|location=Altrincham|pages=117}}</ref>\n*Youngest player: [[Paul Turnbull]], aged 16 years 97 days v [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]], 30 April 2005<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Oldest player: Alec Herd, aged 47 years 40 days vs. Crewe Alexandra, 25 December 1951<ref name=\"Records\" />\n*Most consecutive clean sheets: 9 by [[Wayne Hennessey]], [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]], coinciding with league record for consecutive wins<ref name=\"FL record\" />\n\n===League pyramid statistics===\n''As of season 2019\u201320''<ref name=\"Stockport County datafile\">{{cite news |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1fxPedcqk5r0Ks_LCvN62YNaagn9rGNKPmdh8kBQsq9k/edit#gid=0|title=Stockport County datafile |accessdate=30 August 2015 |publisher=Google Documents}}</ref>\n*Seasons spent at Level 1 of the [[English football league system|football league system]]: 0\n*Seasons spent at Level 2 of the football league system: 26\n*Seasons spent at Level 3 of the football league system: 40\n*Seasons spent at Level 4 of the football league system: 33\n*Seasons spent at Level 5 of the football league system: 3\n*Seasons spent at Level 6 of the football league system: 6\n\n===Nine game winning run===\nStockport County hold the record for the best sequence of results in the [[Football League]], winning nine matches in succession without conceding a goal.<ref name=\"Secret Stockport\" /> This record ran from January to March 2007, when manager [[Jim Gannon]] led the club to the best form shown by a football club in Football League history.<ref name=\"Our History\" /><ref name=\"Stockport County : Records\" /> This final match in this nine match run was a 3\u20130 home win against [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]].<ref name=\"Stockport 3-0 Swindon\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/6408259.stm|title=Stockport 3\u20130 Swindon |accessdate=30 August 2015 |date=3 March 2007  |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nWayne Hennessey, who was on loan to Stockport at the time from Wolves, kept all the clean sheets in his first nine games in professional football.<ref name=\"FL record\" /> He made his footballing debut against [[Boston United F.C.|Boston United]] where Stockport won 2\u20130. During this time, Hennessey received the League Two Player of the Month Award,<ref name=\"Hennessey's heroics secure award\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/stockport/6417015.stm |title=Hennessey's heroics secure award |accessdate=15 April 2012 |date=4 March 2007  |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> The other players involved in matches during the record-breaking run are as follows: [[Robert Clare]], [[Michael Rose (footballer, born 1982)|Michael Rose]], [[Ashley Williams (footballer)|Ashley Williams]], [[Gareth Owen (footballer born 1982)|Gareth Owen]], [[Stephen Gleeson]], [[Jason Taylor (English footballer)|Jason Taylor]], [[Adam Griffin]], [[David Poole (footballer)|David Poole]], [[Damien Allen]], [[Anthony Pilkington]], [[Tony Dinning]], [[Dominic Blizzard]], [[Liam Dickinson]], [[Adam Proudlock]], [[Tes Bramble]] and [[Anthony Elding]].<ref name=\"Stockport County datafile\" />\n\n==Footnotes==\n<sup>1</sup> {{note|TCCnote1}} It can be noted that Hardy was also selected for England for their 1925 tour of Australia while at Stockport, however as these matches were classified as 'test' matches they are not recognised on international records.<ref name=\"England in Australia in 1925\">{{cite web | url=http://sesasport.com/?p=2069 | title= England in Australia in 1925 | publisher= Sports & Editorial Services Australia | date=24 January 2013 |last=Hay|first=Roy | accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>\n<br/>\n<sup>2</sup> {{note|TCCnote2}}It is estimated that between 1,000 and 2,000 people actually attended the match; [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] had played immediately beforehand, and some spectators for that match had stayed on to watch the Stockport match for free. However, only 13 people paid at the gate to watch the Stockport match by itself.<ref name=\"About Stockport County\" /><ref name=\"Programmes\" /><ref name=\"DID YOU KNOW.....PITCHES and what they have had to put up with........\">{{cite news |url=https://www.footballsite.co.uk/DYK/DYK23-Pitches.htm#They%20say%20that%20groundsmen%20would |title=DID YOU KNOW.....PITCHES and what they have had to put up with........|publisher=footballsite.co.uk |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County: A Complete Record |first1=Peter |last1=Freeman|first2=Richard |last2=Harnwell |year=1994 |isbn=1-873626-72-X}}\n*{{cite book |title=Football Fans Guide |first1=Janet |last1=Williams|first2=Mark |last2=Johnson |year=1995 |isbn=978-0002187077}}\n*{{cite book |title=On the Edge: The Official Story of Dave Jones  |first1=David |last1=Jones |year=1997 |isbn=978-1871872255}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County Football Club: An A\u2013Z |first1=Dean |last1=Hayes|year=1998 |isbn=9781850586418}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County \u2013 From the Nursery |first=Peter |last=Freeman |year=1999 |isbn=0-9537558-0-0}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Record of British Wartime Football |first=Brian |last=McColl |year=1999 |isbn=978-1-291-84089-6}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County Encyclopaedia and History Update  |first=Peter |last=Freeman |year=2000 |isbn= 978-1874427636}}\n*{{cite book |title=When Friday Night was County Night: Stockport Footballing Memories |first1=Barry |last1=Cheetham|year=2000 |isbn=978-1850587194}}\n*{{cite book |title=Stockport County 100: The Teams First Season in the Football League 1900\u20131901 |first1=Carol Ann |last1=Perry|year=2000 |isbn=978-0905164748}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888\u20132005 |first1=Paul |last1=Smith|first2=Shirley |last2=Smith |year=2005 |isbn=978-0954783044}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Pictorial History of Stockport County 1883\u20132006 |first1=Richard |last1=Harnwell|first2=Phil |last2=Brennan |year=2006 |isbn=978-0955788918}}\n*{{cite book |title=Legends of Stockport County FC |first=Guy |last=Nelson |year=2008 |isbn= 978-1845471958}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Pictorial History of Stockport County 1883\u20132011 (The Continuing Story) |first1=Richard |last1=Harnwell|first2=Phil |last2=Brennan |year=2011 |isbn=978-0956984869}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Man from Uruguay: Danny Bergara \u2013 A Footballing Journey  |first1=Phil |last1=Brennan |year=2013 |isbn=978-0992785321}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.stockportcounty.com/}}\n*[http://www.historicalkits.co.uk/Stockport_County/Stockport_County.htm List of historical Stockport County kits]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070426213631/http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/towns/stockport3.html details of the crest of Stockport]\n\n{{Stockport County F.C.}}\n{{Stockport County F.C. managers}}\n{{Football Conference}}\n{{Former Football League members}}\n{{Football in Greater Manchester}}\n\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in the Metropolitan Borough of Stockport]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1883]]\n[[Category:1883 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:The Combination]]\n[[Category:Lancashire League (football)]]\n[[Category:Former English Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:Midland Football League (1889)]]\n[[Category:National League (English football)]]\n[[Category:Companies that have entered administration in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Wna247", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1950\u20131999:linked Alan Ogley", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stockport_County_F.C."}
{"title_page": "La Rabouilleuse", "text_new": "{{Infobox book \n| name           = La Rabouilleuse \n| title_orig     = \n| image          = BalzacRabouilleuse01.jpg\n| caption  = Illustration from an 1897 edition<br /> by [[Oreste Cortazzo]]\n| author         = [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]]\n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| series         = [[La Com\u00e9die humaine]]\n| genre          = [[Fiction]]\n| publisher      = Furne\n| release_date   = [[1842 in literature|1842]]\n| media_type     = Print\n| pages          = \n| isbn           = \n| preceded_by    = [[Le Cur\u00e9 de Tours]]\n| followed_by    = [[L'Illustre Gaudissart]]\n}}\n'''''La Rabouilleuse''''' (''The Black Sheep'') is an 1842 novel by [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]], and is one of the ''Sc\u00e8nes de la vie province'' in the series ''[[La Com\u00e9die humaine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/1968|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=''The Human Comedy: Introductions and Appendix''|author=Honor\u00e9 de Balzac|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}</ref> ''The Black Sheep'' is the title of the English translation by [[Donald Adamson]] published by [[Penguin Classics]]. It tells the story of the Bridau family, trying to regain their lost inheritance after a series of mishaps.\n\nThough for years an overlooked work in Balzac's canon, it has gained popularity and respect in recent years. ''[[The Guardian]]'' listed ''The Black Sheep'' 12 on its list of the 100 Greatest Novels of All Time.<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert McCrum |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/oct/12/features.fiction |title=The 100 greatest novels of all time: The list &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |publisher=Guardian |date= 8 August 2006|accessdate=2012-04-16 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe action of the novel is divided between [[Paris]] and [[Issoudun]]. Agathe Rouget, who was born in Issoudun, was sent by her father, Doctor Rouget to be raised by her maternal relatives, the Descoings in Paris. Doctor Rouget suspects (wrongly) that he is not her true father. In Paris, she marries a man named Bridau, and they have two sons, Philippe, and Joseph. Monsieur Bridau dies relatively young, Philippe, who is the eldest and his mother's favourite, becomes a soldier in Napoleon's armies, and Joseph becomes an artist. Philippe, the elder son is shown to be a courageous soldier, but is also a heavy drinker and gambler. He resigns from the army after the [[Bourbon Restoration]] out of loyalty to [[Napoleon]]. Joseph is a dedicated artist, and the more loyal son, but his mother does not understand his artistic vocation.\n\nAfter leaving the army Philippe took part in the failed [[Champ d'Asile]] settlement in Texas. On returning to France he is unemployed, and lives with his mother and Madame Descoings, and becomes a financial drain on them, especially due to his hard drinking and gambling lifestyle. Philippe becomes estranged from his mother and brother after stealing money from Madame Descoings. Philippe is soon afterwards arrested for his involvement in an anti-government conspiracy.\n\nMeanwhile, in Issoudun, Agathe's elder brother Jean-Jacques takes in an ex-soldier named Max Gilet as a boarder. Max is suspected of being his illegitimate half brother. Max and Jean-Jacques' servant Flore Brazier work together to control Jean-Jacques. Max leads a group of young men who call themselves \"The Knights of Idleness\" who frequently play practical jokes around the town. Two of these are against a Spanish immigrant named Fario, destroying his cart and his grain, and therefore ruining his business.\n\nIt is now that Joseph and his mother travel to Issoudun to try to persuade Jean-Jacques to give Agathe money to help cover Philippe's legal costs. They stay with their friends the Hochons. Jean-Jacques and Max only give them some old paintings, but only Joseph recognises their value. Joseph tells of his luck to the Hochons, not realising that their grandsons are friends of Max. Afterwards when Max discovers the value of the paintings he coerces Joseph into returning them. Then one night whilst Max is out walking, he is stabbed by Fario. As Max is recovering he decides to blame Joseph for the stabbing. Joseph is arrested, but later cleared and released, and he and his mother return to Paris.\n\nIn the meantime, Philippe has been convicted for his plotting. However, he cooperates with authorities and gets a light sentence of five years Police supervision in [[Autun]]. Philippe gets his lawyer to change the location to Issoudun in order to claim his mother's inheritance for himself. He challenges Max to a duel with swords, and kills him in the duel. He then takes control of Jean-Jacques and his household, forcing Flore to become Jean-Jacques' wife.\n\nPhilippe marries Flore after the death of Jean-Jacques. Flore dies soon afterwards. The book hints that both of these deaths are arranged by Philippe but is not explicit about the means. Through his connexions, Philippe has now obtained the title Comte de Brambourg. Philippe's attempted marriage to a rich man's daughter falls through when his friends disclose his past to her father. An attempt by Joseph to reconcile Philippe and their mother before her death fails. Philippe's fortunes take a turn for the worse after some unsuccessful speculation, and he rejoins the army to take part in the [[French conquest of Algeria|war in Algeria]] where he is killed in action, so that in the end Joseph, now a successful artist, inherits the family fortune.\n\n==Explanation of title==\n\"La Rabouilleuse\" is the nickname of Flore Brazier used behind her back by the people of Issoudun. Max takes offence when some of his friends use it in conversation. Adamson translates the term as \"the Fisherwoman\". The nickname is a reference to the job that she did as a young girl when helping her uncle to fish for crayfish, by stirring up (to \"rabouiller\") the streamlets.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/17635/17635-h/17635-h.htm|accessdate=7 April 2018|title=''Repertory of the Comedie Humaine'', entry for 'BRIDAU (Flore Brazier, Madame Philippe)'|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}\n</ref> This was before she became a servant to the Rouget household. The English title of the book therefore moves the focus from her to the Bridau brothers.<ref>Adamson, Donald. Translator's Introduction, ''The Black Sheep'', Penguin Classics, 1970</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nIn 1903, [[Emile Fabre]] adapted the story to a play with the same name,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Flat |first=Paul |title=La Rabouilleuse: drame en quatre actes, tir\u00e9 du roman de Balzac |journal=Revue bleue: politique et litt\u00e9raire |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jDsjAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA379 |issue=12 |volume=XIX |date=21 March 1903 |publisher=G. Bailli\u00e8re |language=Fr |page=379 |department=Theatres}}</ref> itself later adapted to two movies called ''Honor of the Family'' ([[The Honor of the Family|in 1912]] and [[Honor of the Family|1931]]). The book was broadcast by [[BBC Radio 4]] as its Classic Serial on Sunday 17 August and Sunday 24 August 2008, with actor [[Geoffrey Whitehead]] as the narrator.\n\nThe French film ''[[The Opportunists (1960 film)|The Opportunists]]'' (1960) is also based on this novel.\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Balzac, Honor\u00e9 de. ''La Rabouilleuse''. 1842.\n* [[Adamson, Donald]]. Translator's Introduction, ''The Black Sheep''. [[Penguin Classics]], 1970, pp.&nbsp;7\u201320.\n* {{in lang|fr}} H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Colombani Giaufret, \u00ab Balzac linguiste dans ''Les C\u00e9libataires'' \u00bb, ''Studi di storia della civilt\u00e0 letteraria francese'', I-II. Paris, Champion, 1996, p.&nbsp;695-717.\n* {{in lang|fr}} Lucienne Frappier-Mazur, \u00ab Max et les Chevaliers : famille, filiation et confr\u00e9rie dans ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Balzac, pater familias'', Amsterdam, Rodopi, 2001, p.&nbsp;51-61.\n* {{in lang|fr}} Gaston Imbault, \u00ab Autour de ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''L'Ann\u00e9e balzacienne'', Paris, Garnier Fr\u00e8res, 1965, p.&nbsp;217-32.\n* Fredric Jameson, \u00ab Imaginary and Symbolic in ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Social Science Information'', 1977, n\u00b0 16, p.&nbsp;59-81.\n* Doris Y. Kadish, \u00ab Landscape, Ideology, and Plot in Balzac's ''Les Chouans'' \u00bb, ''Nineteenth-Century French Studies'', 1984,n\u00b0 12 (3-4), 43-57. \n* Dorothy Magette, \u00ab Trapping Crayfish: The Artist, Nature, and Le Calcul in Balzac\u2019s ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Nineteenth-Century French Studies'', Fall-Winter 1983-1984, n\u00b0 12 (1-2), p.&nbsp;54-67.\n* Allan H. Pasco, \u00ab Process Structure in Balzac\u2019s ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Nineteenth-Century French Studies'', Fall 2005-Winter 2006, n\u00b0 34 (1-2), p.&nbsp;21-31.\n\n{{Honor\u00e9 de Balzac}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rabouilleuse, La}}\n[[Category:1842 French novels]]\n[[Category:Books of La Com\u00e9die humaine]]\n[[Category:Novels by Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book \n| name           = La Rabouilleuse \n| title_orig     = \n| image          = BalzacRabouilleuse01.jpg\n| caption  = Illustration from an 1897 edition<br /> by [[Oreste Cortazzo]]\n| author         = [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]]\n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| series         = [[La Com\u00e9die humaine]]\n| genre          = [[Fiction]]\n| publisher      = Furne\n| release_date   = [[1842 in literature|1842]]\n| media_type     = Print\n| pages          = \n| isbn           = \n| preceded_by    = [[Le Cur\u00e9 de Tours]]\n| followed_by    = [[L'Illustre Gaudissart]]\n}}\n'''''La Rabouilleuse''''' (''The Black Sheep'') is an 1842 novel by [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac]], and is one of the ''Sc\u00e8nes de la vie province'' in the series ''[[La Com\u00e9die humaine]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/1968|accessdate=16 April 2018|title=''The Human Comedy: Introductions and Appendix''|author=Honor\u00e9 de Balzac|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}</ref> ''The Black Sheep'' is the title of the English translation by [[Donald Adamson]] published by [[Penguin Classics]]. It tells the story of the Bridau family, trying to regain their lost inheritance after a series of mishaps.\n\nThough for years an overlooked work in Balzac's canon, it has gained popularity and respect in recent years. ''[[The Guardian]]'' listed ''The Black Sheep'' 12 on its list of the 100 Greatest Novels of All Time.<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert McCrum |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/oct/12/features.fiction |title=The 100 greatest novels of all time: The list &#124; Books &#124; The Observer |publisher=Guardian |date= 8 August 2006|accessdate=2012-04-16 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nThe action of the novel is divided between [[Paris]] and [[Issoudun]]. Agathe Rouget, who was born in Issoudun, was sent by her father, Doctor Rouget to be raised by her maternal relatives, the Descoings in Paris. Doctor Rouget suspects (wrongly) that he is not her true father. In Paris, she marries a man named Bridau, and they have two sons, Philippe, and Joseph. Monsieur Bridau dies relatively young, Philippe, who is the eldest and his mother's favourite, becomes a soldier in Napoleon's armies, and Joseph becomes an artist. Philippe, the elder son is shown to be a courageous soldier, but is also a heavy drinker and gambler. He resigns from the army after the [[Bourbon Restoration]] out of loyalty to [[Napoleon]]. Joseph is a dedicated artist, and the more loyal son, but his mother does not understand his artistic vocation.\n\nAfter leaving the army Philippe took part in the failed [[Champ d'Asile]] settlement in Texas. On returning to France he is unemployed, and lives with his mother and Madame Descoings, and becomes a financial drain on them, especially due to his hard drinking and gambling lifestyle. Philippe becomes estranged from his mother and brother after stealing money from Madame Descoings. Philippe is soon afterwards arrested for his involvement in an anti-government conspiracy.\n\nMeanwhile, in Issoudun, Agathe's elder brother Jean-Jacques takes in an ex-soldier named Max Gilet as a boarder. Max is suspected of being his illegitimate half brother. Max and Jean-Jacques' servant Flore Brazier work together to control Jean-Jacques. Max leads a group of young men who call themselves \"The Knights of Idleness\" who frequently play practical jokes around the town. Two of these are against a Spanish immigrant named Fario, destroying his cart and his grain, and therefore ruining his business.\n\nIt is now that Joseph and his mother travel to Issoudun to try to persuade Jean-Jacques to give Agathe money to help cover Philippe's legal costs. They stay with their friends the Hochons. Jean-Jacques and Max only give them some old paintings, but only Joseph recognises their value. Joseph tells of his luck to the Hochons, not realising that their grandsons are friends of Max. Afterwards when Max discovers the value of the paintings he coerces Joseph into returning them. Then one night whilst Max is out walking, he is stabbed by Fario. As Max is recovering he decides to blame Joseph for the stabbing. Joseph is arrested, but later cleared and released, and he and his mother return to Paris.\n\nIn the meantime, Philippe has been convicted for his plotting. However, he cooperates with authorities and gets a light sentence of five years Police supervision in [[Autun]]. Philippe gets his lawyer to change the location to Issoudun in order to claim his mother's inheritance for himself. He challenges Max to a duel with swords, and kills him in the duel. He then takes control of Jean-Jacques and his household, forcing Flore to become Jean-Jacques' wife.\n\nPhilippe marries Flore after the death of Jean-Jacques. Flore,too , soon dies. The book hints that both of these deaths are arranged by Philippe but is not explicit about the means. Through his connexions, Philippe has now obtained the title Comte de Brambourg. Philippe's attempted marriage to a rich man's daughter falls through when his friends disclose his past to her father. An attempt by Joseph to reconcile Philippe and their mother before her death fails. Philippe's fortunes take a turn for the worse after some unsuccessful speculation, and he rejoins the army to take part in the [[French conquest of Algeria|war in Algeria]] where he is killed in action, so that in the end Joseph, now a successful artist, inherits the family fortune.\n\n==Explanation of title==\n\"La Rabouilleuse\" is the nickname of Flore Brazier used behind her back by the people of Issoudun. Max takes offence when some of his friends use it in conversation. Adamson translates the term as \"the Fisherwoman\". The nickname is a reference to the job that she did as a young girl when helping her uncle to fish for crayfish, by stirring up (to \"rabouiller\") the streamlets.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/17635/17635-h/17635-h.htm|accessdate=7 April 2018|title=''Repertory of the Comedie Humaine'', entry for 'BRIDAU (Flore Brazier, Madame Philippe)'|publisher=Project Gutenberg}}\n</ref> This was before she became a servant to the Rouget household. The English title of the book therefore moves the focus from her to the Bridau brothers.<ref>Adamson, Donald. Translator's Introduction, ''The Black Sheep'', Penguin Classics, 1970</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\nIn 1903, [[Emile Fabre]] adapted the story to a play with the same name,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Flat |first=Paul |title=La Rabouilleuse: drame en quatre actes, tir\u00e9 du roman de Balzac |journal=Revue bleue: politique et litt\u00e9raire |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jDsjAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA379 |issue=12 |volume=XIX |date=21 March 1903 |publisher=G. Bailli\u00e8re |language=Fr |page=379 |department=Theatres}}</ref> itself later adapted to two movies called ''Honor of the Family'' ([[The Honor of the Family|in 1912]] and [[Honor of the Family|1931]]). The book was broadcast by [[BBC Radio 4]] as its Classic Serial on Sunday 17 August and Sunday 24 August 2008, with actor [[Geoffrey Whitehead]] as the narrator.\n\nThe French film ''[[The Opportunists (1960 film)|The Opportunists]]'' (1960) is also based on this novel.\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Balzac, Honor\u00e9 de. ''La Rabouilleuse''. 1842.\n* [[Adamson, Donald]]. Translator's Introduction, ''The Black Sheep''. [[Penguin Classics]], 1970, pp.&nbsp;7\u201320.\n* {{in lang|fr}} H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Colombani Giaufret, \u00ab Balzac linguiste dans ''Les C\u00e9libataires'' \u00bb, ''Studi di storia della civilt\u00e0 letteraria francese'', I-II. Paris, Champion, 1996, p.&nbsp;695-717.\n* {{in lang|fr}} Lucienne Frappier-Mazur, \u00ab Max et les Chevaliers : famille, filiation et confr\u00e9rie dans ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Balzac, pater familias'', Amsterdam, Rodopi, 2001, p.&nbsp;51-61.\n* {{in lang|fr}} Gaston Imbault, \u00ab Autour de ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''L'Ann\u00e9e balzacienne'', Paris, Garnier Fr\u00e8res, 1965, p.&nbsp;217-32.\n* Fredric Jameson, \u00ab Imaginary and Symbolic in ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Social Science Information'', 1977, n\u00b0 16, p.&nbsp;59-81.\n* Doris Y. Kadish, \u00ab Landscape, Ideology, and Plot in Balzac's ''Les Chouans'' \u00bb, ''Nineteenth-Century French Studies'', 1984,n\u00b0 12 (3-4), 43-57. \n* Dorothy Magette, \u00ab Trapping Crayfish: The Artist, Nature, and Le Calcul in Balzac\u2019s ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Nineteenth-Century French Studies'', Fall-Winter 1983-1984, n\u00b0 12 (1-2), p.&nbsp;54-67.\n* Allan H. Pasco, \u00ab Process Structure in Balzac\u2019s ''La Rabouilleuse'' \u00bb, ''Nineteenth-Century French Studies'', Fall 2005-Winter 2006, n\u00b0 34 (1-2), p.&nbsp;21-31.\n\n{{Honor\u00e9 de Balzac}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n