lldogs football coach navbox}}\n{{2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2011 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Sporting News College Football Coach of the Year}}\n{{AFCA Assistant Coach of the Year}}\n{{Broyles Award}}\n{{George Munger Award}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smart, Kirby}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football coaches]]\n[[Category:American football defensive backs]]\n[[Category:Florida State Seminoles football coaches]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football coaches]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Miami Dolphins coaches]]\n[[Category:Valdosta State Blazers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Florida State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Bainbridge, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Montgomery, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "2601:483:4701:240:3484:89b4:cacd:7164", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirby_Smart"}
{"title_page": "John Schroeder (musician)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = John Schroeder\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          =  \n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = John Francis Schroeder \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = 19 January 1935\n| birth_place         = [[London]], England\n| death_date          =  {{Death date|2017|1|31|df=yes}} (aged 82)\n| death_place         =\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[Easy listening]], pop\n| occupation          = Composer, arranger, record producer, songwriter\n| years_active        = 1960s-2016\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{url|www.johnschroeder.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''John Francis Schroeder''' (19 January 1935<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sex-Violins-Affair-Life-Music-ebook/dp/B00N23THCY/ref=sr_1_sc_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1489268831&sr=8-1-spell&keywords=john+scroeder+sex#reader_B00N23THCY |title=''Sex and Violins: My Affair with Life Love and Music'' |author=John Schroeder |website=Amazon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-03-12}}</ref> \u2013 31 January 2017)<ref>[http://www.cymandeofficial.com/  John Schroeder, ''cymandeofficial.com'']. Retrieved 3 February 2017</ref> was a British [[pop music|pop]] and [[easy listening]] composer, arranger, songwriter and record producer. In 1961, Schroeder won an [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for co-writing \"[[Walkin' Back to Happiness]]\".<ref name=\"John\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnschroeder.co.uk/pages/recordingcareer.html |title=John Schroeder, Alaska Records, Pye, Oriole, Oriole American, Sounds Orchestral, Helen Shapiro, Status Quo, Mersey Beat |publisher=Johnschroeder.co.uk |date=4 December 1961 |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nSchroeder worked as an [[A&R]] assistant to [[Norrie Paramor]] at [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia Records]]. He was also a songwriter and, with [[Mike Hawker (songwriter)|Mike Hawker]], wrote the song \"[[Walkin' Back to Happiness]]\", which in a version by [[Helen Shapiro]] reached number one in the [[UK Singles Chart]] during 1961.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 494}}</ref> Schroeder also co-wrote two other hits for Shapiro, \"[[Don't Treat Me Like a Child]]\", a UK number 3 and \"[[You Don't Know (Helen Shapiro song)|You Don't Know]]\", which also reached number 1 in August 1961.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.spectropop.com/JohnSchroeder/index.htm |title=John Schroeder |publisher=Spectropop.com |date= |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nLater he moved to independent British label, [[Oriole Records (UK)|Oriole]] as A&R chief, and whilst he was there he brokered an early [[licensing]] deal with [[Motown]] for British distribution on the label.<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|last=Unterberger |first=Richie |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-schroeder-mn0000525305 |title=John Schroeder \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> It subsequently issued such [[single (music)|singles]] as [[The Contours]]' \"[[Do You Love Me]]\" and \"[[Fingertips]]\" by [[Stevie Wonder|Little Stevie Wonder]].<ref name=\"John\"/>\n\nIn the mid 1960s, Schroeder moved to [[Pye Records|Pye]] and formed the [[instrumental]] pop outfit [[Sounds Orchestral]] with [[Johnny Pearson]].  They had an international [[hit record|hit]] with their [[cover version|version]] of \"[[Cast Your Fate to the Wind]]\", which included reaching No. 5 in the UK chart.<ref name=\"AMG\"/><ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums 2\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 516}}</ref> With this group as well as under several other names, including his own, he released a large number of [[easy listening]] [[cover version|covers]] of popular songs. While many of these saw little critical acclaim upon release, there was a resurgence in interest in them in the 1990s, when they became popular tracks in London dance clubs,<ref name=\"AMG\"/> and appeared on soundtracks to films such as the ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' franchise.\n\nDuring his tenure with Pye, Schroeder oversaw their [[Pye Records|Piccadilly]] subsidiary label, producing singles by artists such as [[Keith (Powell) & Billie Davis (duo)|Keith & Billie]] on \"[[Swingin' Tight]]\"<ref>web|url=http://www.brumbeat.net/valets.htm</ref> and eventually launching the career (after several false starts) of [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]], beginning in 1968 with their first hit, \"[[Pictures of Matchstick Men]]\".<ref name=\"John\"/>\n\nIn the early 1970s, John Schroeder started Alaska Records, best known for the label's work with [[Cymande]].<ref name=\"John\"/> and produced \"Hands Across The Sea\", which was one of [[The Dooleys]] earliest recordings, written by Ben Findon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/The-Dooley-Family-Hands-Across-The-Sea-Oo-Pa-Pa-Doo/release/5458665|title=The Dooley Family* - Hands Across The Sea / Oo-Pa-Pa-Doo|website=Discogs|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> The Alaska label was subsequently joined by another founded by Schroeder, [[Janus Records]]. In the early 1980s, John Schroeder moved to Canada, living and working there until the early 1990s. He started Centamark International with Gary Bizzo in Vancouver as consultants to the music industry in 1981.\n\nHe later lived in [[Surrey]], England. His autobiography, ''Sex and Violins'' was published in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PvGWYgEACAAJ&dq=John+Schroeder.+sex+and+violins&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6AfqUJV9ypPRBa2FgcAE&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA |title=Sex and Violins: \"My Affair with Life, Love and Music\" \u2013 John Schroeder \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref> Two years later, Schroeder again became an author, writing and publishing a second book titled, ''Cozy Cats Cottage plc''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0sWEubXJB0cC&pg=PR3&dq=John+Schroeder.+sex+and+violins&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6AfqUJV9ypPRBa2FgcAE&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Schroeder.%20sex%20and%20violins&f=false |title=Cozy Cats Cottage Plc \u2013 John Schroeder \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref> This book is unrelated to the [[music industry]] and told the story of fictional character Angela Tillsworthy, and how she formed a company employing friendly cats to help the needy. It was published in 2011.\n\n==Death==\nJohn Schroeder died at his home on 31 January 2017 after a long battle with cancer. He was 82 years old. His funeral took place at Randall's Park Crematorium on 3 March 2017.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n*''Working in the Soul Mine'' ([[Pye Records|Pye]], 1966)\n*''The Dolly Catcher'' ([[Piccadilly Records|Piccadilly]], 1967)\n*''Witchi-Tai-To'' (Pye, 1971)\n*''You've Made Me So Very Happy'' ([[Marble Arch Records|Marble Arch]], 1971)\n*''Dylan Vibrations'' ([[Polydor Records|Polydor]], 1972)\n*''Latin Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1971)\n*''Love Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)\n*''Party Dance Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)\n*''T.V. Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)\n*''Gangster Movie Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)<ref name=\"AMG\"/><ref name=\"Disc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/John+Schroeder |title=John Schroeder Discography at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Soul for Sale\" (Pye, 1966)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orch-Youve-Lost-That-Lovin-Feeling-Soul-For-Sale/release/3160402 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra \u2013 You've Lost That Lovin' Feeling / Soul For Sale (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"The Fugitive Theme\" (Piccadilly, 1965)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orch-Youve-Lost-That-Lovin-Feeling-Soul-For-Sale/release/3954857 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra, The \u2013 The Fugitive Theme (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"On The Ball (World Cup Theme)\" (Pye, 1966)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-On-The-Ball/release/3934159 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra, The \u2013 On The Ball (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"Wanna Thank You Girl\" (Pye, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Wanna-Thank-You-Girl/release/2703787 |title=John Schroeder \u2013 Wanna Thank You Girl (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"One Way Glass\" (Pye, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-One-Way-Glass/release/2971341 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra* \u2013 One Way Glass (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"I'm Gonna Change\" (Alaska, 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-Im-Gonna-Change-First-Love/release/2308125 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra* \u2013 I'm Gonna Change / First Love (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"All Night\" (Alaska, 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-All-Night/release/2314958 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra* \u2013 All Night (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Publishing==\n*2009: ''Sex and Violins'' \u2013 {{ISBN|1906710643}}\n*2011: ''Cozy Cats Cottage plc'' \u2013 {{ISBN|978-1848767-225}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johnschroeder.co.uk Official website]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/john-silke/john-schroeder-60s-producer John Schroeder interview 2012]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/zazie-dans-le-metro/john-schroeder-interview-on-sounds-orchestral John Schroeder Interview 2015]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schroeder, John}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:British music arrangers]]\n[[Category:British pop musicians]]\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:British songwriters]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name                = John Schroeder\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| image_size          =  \n| background          = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name          = John Francis Schroeder \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = 19 January 1935\n| birth_place         = [[London]], England\n| death_date          =  {{Death date|2017|1|31|df=yes}} (aged 82)\n| death_place         =\n| instrument          = \n| genre               = [[Easy listening]], pop\n| occupation          = Composer, arranger, record producer, songwriter\n| years_active        = 1960s-2016\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{url|www.johnschroeder.co.uk}}\n}}\n\n'''John Francis Schroeder''' (19 January 1935<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Sex-Violins-Affair-Life-Music-ebook/dp/B00N23THCY/ref=sr_1_sc_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1489268831&sr=8-1-spell&keywords=john+scroeder+sex#reader_B00N23THCY |title=''Sex and Violins: My Affair with Life Love and Music'' |author=John Schroeder |website=Amazon.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-03-12}}</ref> \u2013 31 January 2017)<ref>[http://www.cymandeofficial.com/  John Schroeder, ''cymandeofficial.com'']. Retrieved 3 February 2017</ref> was a British [[pop music|pop]] and [[easy listening]] composer, arranger, songwriter and record producer. In 1961, Schroeder won an [[Ivor Novello Awards|Ivor Novello Award]] for co-writing \"[[Walkin' Back to Happiness]]\".<ref name=\"John\">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnschroeder.co.uk/pages/recordingcareer.html |title=John Schroeder, Alaska Records, Pye, Oriole, Oriole American, Sounds Orchestral, Helen Shapiro, Status Quo, Mersey Beat |publisher=Johnschroeder.co.uk |date=4 December 1961 |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nSchroeder worked as an [[A&R]] assistant to [[Norrie Paramor]] at [[Columbia Graphophone Company|Columbia Records]]. He was also a songwriter and, with [[Mike Hawker (songwriter)|Mike Hawker]], wrote the song \"[[Walkin' Back to Happiness]]\", which in a version by [[Helen Shapiro]] reached number one in the [[UK Singles Chart]] during 1961.<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 494}}</ref> Schroeder also co-wrote two other hits for Shapiro, \"[[Don't Treat Me Like a Child]]\", a UK number 3 and \"[[You Don't Know (Helen Shapiro song)|You Don't Know]]\", which also reached number 1 in August 1961.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.spectropop.com/JohnSchroeder/index.htm |title=John Schroeder |publisher=Spectropop.com |date= |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nLater he moved to independent British label, [[Oriole Records (UK)|Oriole]] as A&R chief, and whilst he was there he brokered an early [[licensing]] deal with [[Motown]] for British distribution on the label.<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|last=Unterberger |first=Richie |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-schroeder-mn0000525305 |title=John Schroeder \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> It subsequently issued such [[single (music)|singles]] as [[The Contours]]' \"[[Do You Love Me]]\" and \"[[Fingertips]]\" by [[Stevie Wonder|Little Stevie Wonder]].<ref name=\"John\"/>\n\nIn the mid 1960s, Schroeder moved to [[Pye Records|Pye]] and formed the [[instrumental]] pop outfit [[Sounds Orchestral]] with [[Johnny Pearson]].  They had an international [[hit record|hit]] with their [[cover version|version]] of \"[[Cast Your Fate to the Wind]]\", which included reaching No. 5 in the UK chart.<ref name=\"AMG\"/><ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums 2\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited \n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 516}}</ref> With this group as well as under several other names, including his own, he released a large number of [[easy listening]] [[cover version|covers]] of popular songs. While many of these saw little critical acclaim upon release, there was a resurgence in interest in them in the 1990s, when they became popular tracks in London dance clubs,<ref name=\"AMG\"/> and appeared on soundtracks to films such as the ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' franchise.\n\nDuring his tenure with Pye, Schroeder oversaw their [[Pye Records|Piccadilly]] subsidiary label, eventually launching the career (after several false starts) of [[Status Quo (band)|Status Quo]], beginning in 1968 with their first hit, \"[[Pictures of Matchstick Men]]\".<ref name=\"John\"/>\n\nIn the early 1970s, John Schroeder started Alaska Records, best known for the label's work with [[Cymande]].<ref name=\"John\"/> and produced \"Hands Across The Sea\", which was one of [[The Dooleys]] earliest recordings, written by Ben Findon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/The-Dooley-Family-Hands-Across-The-Sea-Oo-Pa-Pa-Doo/release/5458665|title=The Dooley Family* - Hands Across The Sea / Oo-Pa-Pa-Doo|website=Discogs|accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref> The Alaska label was subsequently joined by another founded by Schroeder, [[Janus Records]]. In the early 1980s, John Schroeder moved to Canada, living and working there until the early 1990s. He started Centamark International with Gary Bizzo in Vancouver as consultants to the music industry in 1981.\n\nHe later lived in [[Surrey]], England. His autobiography, ''Sex and Violins'' was published in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PvGWYgEACAAJ&dq=John+Schroeder.+sex+and+violins&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6AfqUJV9ypPRBa2FgcAE&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA |title=Sex and Violins: \"My Affair with Life, Love and Music\" \u2013 John Schroeder \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref> Two years later, Schroeder again became an author, writing and publishing a second book titled, ''Cozy Cats Cottage plc''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0sWEubXJB0cC&pg=PR3&dq=John+Schroeder.+sex+and+violins&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6AfqUJV9ypPRBa2FgcAE&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=John%20Schroeder.%20sex%20and%20violins&f=false |title=Cozy Cats Cottage Plc \u2013 John Schroeder \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref> This book is unrelated to the [[music industry]] and told the story of fictional character Angela Tillsworthy, and how she formed a company employing friendly cats to help the needy. It was published in 2011.\n\n==Death==\nJohn Schroeder died at his home on 31 January 2017 after a long battle with cancer. He was 82 years old. His funeral took place at Randall's Park Crematorium on 3 March 2017.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n*''Working in the Soul Mine'' ([[Pye Records|Pye]], 1966)\n*''The Dolly Catcher'' ([[Piccadilly Records|Piccadilly]], 1967)\n*''Witchi-Tai-To'' (Pye, 1971)\n*''You've Made Me So Very Happy'' ([[Marble Arch Records|Marble Arch]], 1971)\n*''Dylan Vibrations'' ([[Polydor Records|Polydor]], 1972)\n*''Latin Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1971)\n*''Love Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)\n*''Party Dance Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)\n*''T.V. Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)\n*''Gangster Movie Vibrations'' (Polydor, 1972)<ref name=\"AMG\"/><ref name=\"Disc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/artist/John+Schroeder |title=John Schroeder Discography at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Soul for Sale\" (Pye, 1966)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orch-Youve-Lost-That-Lovin-Feeling-Soul-For-Sale/release/3160402 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra \u2013 You've Lost That Lovin' Feeling / Soul For Sale (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"The Fugitive Theme\" (Piccadilly, 1965)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orch-Youve-Lost-That-Lovin-Feeling-Soul-For-Sale/release/3954857 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra, The \u2013 The Fugitive Theme (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"On The Ball (World Cup Theme)\" (Pye, 1966)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-On-The-Ball/release/3934159 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra, The \u2013 On The Ball (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"Wanna Thank You Girl\" (Pye, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Wanna-Thank-You-Girl/release/2703787 |title=John Schroeder \u2013 Wanna Thank You Girl (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"One Way Glass\" (Pye, 1971)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-One-Way-Glass/release/2971341 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra* \u2013 One Way Glass (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"I'm Gonna Change\" (Alaska, 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-Im-Gonna-Change-First-Love/release/2308125 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra* \u2013 I'm Gonna Change / First Love (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n*\"All Night\" (Alaska, 1975)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/John-Schroeder-Orchestra-All-Night/release/2314958 |title=John Schroeder Orchestra* \u2013 All Night (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Publishing==\n*2009: ''Sex and Violins'' \u2013 {{ISBN|1906710643}}\n*2011: ''Cozy Cats Cottage plc'' \u2013 {{ISBN|978-1848767-225}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.johnschroeder.co.uk Official website]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/john-silke/john-schroeder-60s-producer John Schroeder interview 2012]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/zazie-dans-le-metro/john-schroeder-interview-on-sounds-orchestral John Schroeder Interview 2015]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schroeder, John}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:British music arrangers]]\n[[Category:British pop musicians]]\n[[Category:British record producers]]\n[[Category:British songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "Artastic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Addition of Keith & Billie", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Schroeder_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Georgia Godwin", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian artistic gymnast}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox gymnast\n| name = Georgia Godwin\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| fullname =\n| nickname =\n| country = {{AUS}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1997|10|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Southport, Queensland]], Australia\n| hometown = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| discipline = WAG\n| level =\n| natlteam =\n| club = \n| headcoach = \n| show-medals = yes \n| medaltemplates = <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] -->\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic individual all-around|All-Around]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic team all-around|Team]] }}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's uneven bars|Uneven Bars]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Georgia Godwin''' (born 28 October 1997) is an Australian artistic gymnast.<ref name=2018cgresults />\n\nBorn in [[Southport, Queensland]],<ref name=2018cgresults>{{cite web |title=Artistic Gymnastics {{!}} Athlete Profile: Georgia GODWIN - Gold Coast 2018 Commonwealth Games |url=https://results.gc2018.com/en/artistic-gymnastics/athlete-profile-n6029339-georgia-godwin.htm?source=mobile_app |website=results.gc2018.com |accessdate=3 August 2018 |language=en-AU}}</ref> Godwin represented Australia at the [[2017 Artistic Gymnastics World Championships]], finishing in 13th place.<ref>{{cite web |title=Georgia Godwin |url=http://commonwealthgames.com.au/athletes/georgia-godwin/ |website=commonwealthgames.com.au |accessdate=3 August 2018 |language=en-AU |date=1984}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she participated in the [[2018 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] where she won a silver medal in the [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic individual all-around|individual all-around]] event and bronze medals in the [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic team all-around|team all-around]] and [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's uneven bars|uneven bars]] events.<ref name=2018cgresults />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FIG|lic=24003|bio=39507|name=Georgia Godwin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Godwin, Georgia}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female artistic gymnasts]]\n[[Category:Gymnasts at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in gymnastics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for Australia]]\n{{Australia-artistic-gymnastics-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian artistic gymnast}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox gymnast\n| name = Georgia Godwin\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption = \n| fullname =\n| nickname =\n| country = {{AUS}}\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1997|10|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Southport, Queensland]], Australia\n| hometown = \n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| height = \n| discipline = WAG\n| level =\n| natlteam =\n| club = \n| headcoach = \n| show-medals = yes \n| medaltemplates = <!-- see [[Template:MedalRelatedTemplates]] -->\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic individual all-around|All-Around]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic team all-around|Team]] }}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Gold Coast]] | [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's uneven bars|Uneven Bars]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Georgia Godwin''' (born 28 October 1997) is an Australian artistic gymnast.<ref name=2018cgresults />\n\nBorn in [[Southport, Queensland]],<ref name=2018cgresults>{{cite web |title=Artistic Gymnastics {{!}} Athlete Profile: Georgia GODWIN - Gold Coast 2018 Commonwealth Games |url=https://results.gc2018.com/en/artistic-gymnastics/athlete-profile-n6029339-georgia-godwin.htm?source=mobile_app |website=results.gc2018.com |accessdate=3 August 2018 |language=en-AU}}</ref> Godwin represented Australia at the [[2017 Artistic Gymnastics World Championships]], finishing in 13th place.<ref>{{cite web |title=Georgia Godwin |url=http://commonwealthgames.com.au/athletes/georgia-godwin/ |website=commonwealthgames.com.au |accessdate=3 August 2018 |language=en-AU |date=1984}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she participated in the [[2018 Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]] where she won a silver medal in the [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic individual all-around|individual all-around]] event and bronze medals in the [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's artistic team all-around|team all-around]] and [[Gymnastics at the 2018 Commonwealth Games \u2013 Women's uneven bars|uneven bars]] events.<ref name=2018cgresults />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FIG|lic=24003|bio=39507|name=Georgia Godwin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Godwin, Georgia}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female artistic gymnasts]]\n[[Category:Gymnasts at the 2018 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in gymnastics]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for Australia]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games bronze medallists for Australia]]\n{{Australia-artistic-gymnastics-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Suonii180", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georgia_Godwin"}
